<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
news items in leading U.S. newspapers:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times
</P>
<P>
-- Attorney General Janet Reno has opened a formal inquiry into
whether President Clinton illegally solicited campaign
contributions in telephone calls from the White House last year.
</P>
<P>
The action is a potential turning point in the sprawling
campaign finance inquiry surrounding his re-election campaign, a
step that could lead to the appointment of an independent
prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
-- An account of the voyage of a gray-bearded Italian Jewish
sailor named Jacob places him in China four years before Marco
Polo arrived. If the document is to be believed, it provides
extraordinary images of a civilization that was the most dazzling
in the world, describing everything from mass-circulation
pornography to an early flame thrower.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post
</P>
<P>
-- A bipartisan advisory commission will urge Congress to
reform the nation's system for admitting immigrants to give
priority to close family members who have been separated for years
because of growing waits for visas.
</P>
<P>
-- The U.S. decision not to sign the treaty on land mines ban is
being described by White House and Pentagon officials as an
indication the once-rocky relationship between the president and
military leaders has, on many key issues, been transformed into a
dependable working partnership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
