<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Taliban Forces Claim Recapture of Border Town </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Forces opposing the Afghan
Islamic Taliban militia today claimed that they had recaptured the
key border town of Hairatan, which separates Afghanistan from its
Central Asian neighbor Uzbekistan.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban fighters, who entered Hairatan early Thursday, had
been pushed out of the dusty town center by the anti-Taliban
alliance forces, said Afghan sources in Peshawar, northwestern
Pakistan, without giving details on when the counterattack took
place.
</P>
<P>
However, Taliban sources in Peshawar denied the claim but
admitted that the hardline student militia had suffered heavy
losses in repulsing the alliance's offensive.
</P>
<P>
Hairatan, situated 60 kilometers north of Mazar-e-Sharif,
stronghold of the alliance, is a key town on the Uzbekistan border
and located on the banks of the Amu Darya (Oxus River).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the United Nations and the Red Cross have evacuated
more than 50 foreign aid workers from the embattled
Mazar-e-Sharif, 300 kilometers north of Kabul, capital of
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The foreigners had been trapped in Mazar-e-Sharif since the
Taliban, who control two-thirds of Afghan territory and the
capital of Kabul, launched a strong attack on the city early this
month.
</P>
<P>
According to U.N. officials, the U.N. offices in Mazar-e-Sharif
were looted by gun-toting youths and losses were estimated at
millions of U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, who have vowed to impose a strict Islamic rule in
the war-torn country, briefly controlled Mazar-e-Sharif, but were
forced to retreat later.
</P>
<P>
The anti-Taliban alliance, which comprises forces led by Uzbek
warlord Abdul Malik, Afghanistan's former military chief Ahmad
Masood and the Shiite Hezb-e-Wadhat, has been battling the Islamic
militia in several fronts in northern, central and western
Afghanistan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
