<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab Foreign Ministers Doubtful Over Regional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Arab foreign ministers are
sceptical over the success of a regional economic summit scheduled
for November in Doha, Qatar, Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
said today.
</P>
<P>
After their three-day Arab League (AL) council meeting, the
foreign ministers failed to reached a single stand towards the
Middle East and North Africa summit which has been criticized for
Israeli attendance.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's Middle East News Agency quoted Moussa as saying that
"if the Israeli government does not change its policies (towards
peace), I think that prospects for the success of the conference
would be slim."
</P>
<P>
The Doha summit was not mentioned in a final statement issued
after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, the foreign ministers strongly condemned
Israeli "ferocious" settlement activities in Arab Jerusalem and
the rest of the occupied Arab territories.
</P>
<P>
They underlined the need of boosting the peace process and
continuing it on the basis of U.N. resolutions concerned, the
land-for-peace principle and the right of the Palestinians for
self determination.
</P>
<P>
They urged the international community, particularly the United
States and Russia, the co-sponsors of the Mideast peace and the
European Union to press Israel in honoring its peace promises.
</P>
<P>
Welcoming U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright's visit to
the region earlier this month, the final statement described as
"constructive position" her policy on Mideast peace.
</P>
<P>
But the foreign ministers condemned U.S. Congress resolution
passed in June to recognize Jerusalem a capital of Israel, a city
also claimed by Palestinians as the capital of their future
state. They also denounced another U.S. Congress decision to move
the U.S. embassy from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
