<HEADLINE> Somalis Should Solve Their Own Problems: US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The Somali faction led by
Hussein Aidid said they received a letter from the American
government last night, stating that the Somalis should solve
their internal problems alone without intervention.
</P>
<P>
According to local radio today, in the letter the American
government said they don't support the attitude of the Sodare
group, the factions that recently formed the National Salvation
Council (NSC) in Sodare village of Ethiopia, and the
administration they would establish in the northeastern town of
Bossaso this November.
</P>
<P>
The American government believes that the Somalis should solve
their internal problems alone without any intervention, said the
radio.
</P>
<P>
The statement broadcast came at a time when the Sodare
factions are preparing themselves for the anticipated conference
in the northeastern town of Bossaso in early November.
</P>
<P>
The radio said the letter was brought to the representative of
Hussein Aidid in Nairobi by Theodore Andrews, the liaison officer
for Somali affairs in the American embassy in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
The letter was also conveyed to Foreign Minister of Hussein
Aidid, Jama Mohamed Qalib, in Djibouti through the American
embassy there, the radio added.
</P>
<P>
However, many people in Mogadishu wondered what had changed in
the American policy and in their former attitude, while many
others noted that the allegations in the radio broadcast are
baseless.
</P>
<P>
But there is no independent confirmation regarding the matter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
