<DOCNO> XIE19970922.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Confiscates 2 Dutch Vessels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Iran announced here today
that two Dutch vessels were confiscated by the Iranian security
guards at Iman Khomeini port last week.
</P>
<P>
Mohammad Madad, head of the Ports and Shipping Organization,
said that his country took the action because the Dutch vessels
violated international regulations.
</P>
<P>
He said that after a Croatian cargo ship sank in Iran's
territorial waters, the Smit Tug Company of the Netherlands was
given the responsibility of pulling the ship out of the sea.
</P>
<P>
Madad said that any movement of the Dutch vessels should have
been with full knowledge and authorization of Iranian
authorities.
</P>
<P>
On August 19, the two Dutch vessels abandoned the mission and
headed for another part of the sea to pull out the debris of a
U.S. helicopter crashed in Iran's territorial waters.
</P>
<P>
Madad said his organization filed a complaint with Iran's
Judiciary against the Smit Tug Company and the judicial officials
issued a warrant for confiscation of the two vessels.
</P>
<P>
He added that the crew of the tugboats would be allowed to
contact their families immediately after completion of the legal
process.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Peter C. Fit, special envoy of Dutch Foreign
Ministry, was quoted by the official news agency IRNA as saying
that the Smit Tug Company had not any malicious intentions
against Iran.
</P>
<P>
Fit offered compensation for the damage the Iranian shipping
organization incurred and expressed the hope that the problem
would be resolved soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
