<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone Junta Shortens Curfew </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The military junta in Sierra
Leone has announced a two-hour reduction of the curfew in force
as from Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The government radio did not give any reason for the measure,
which means the curfew will now start at midnight instead of
10:00 p.m., and run until 6:00 a.m.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a report reaching here today quoted sources close
to the Foreign Ministry as disclosing the imminent arrival of a
new United Nations envoy, Francis Okelo, a Ugandan who was
formerly with the U.N. delegation in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The sources also said that United States Ambassador John
Hirsch could return to the Sierra Leonean capital of Freetown
soon for talks with the ruling junta on a return to
constitutional legality in the country.
</P>
<P>
All foreign embassies closed their doors in protest after
coupists toppled the legitimate government on May 25 this year
which moved to neighboring Guinea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
