<DOCNO> XIE19970922.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Should Build its Own Defense Industry: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Turkey should double efforts
to speed up building its own defense industry, Defense Minister
Ismet Sezgin said today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the press in Istanbul, the largest city in Turkey,
Sezgin said that the past lessons demand Turkey should have its
own defense industry, the semi-official Anatolia News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
He recalled that the allied countries had reduced their
military support to Turkey in recent years due to different
disputes with Ankara.
</P>
<P>
Turkey was greatly angered when the United States suspended
last year the delivery of three frigates ordered by the Turkish
Navy, under strong pressure from anti-Turkish lobbies.
</P>
<P>
Sezgin, also deputy prime minister, emphasized that this
urged Turkey to speed up building its own defense industry in an
effort to enhance its defense capacity in the future.
</P>
<P>
The Defense Industry Support Fund and the Defense Industry
Undersecretariat had been founded just for this purpose, he
said.
</P>
<P>
On the Third International Defense Industry and Civil Aviation
Fair to be held here on September 23-26, Sezgin said that this
will strengthen the exchanges between Turkish and foreign
companies in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, a regional military power, has to import nearly 80
percent of its arms from Western countries to meet the demands
of the Turkish Armed Force, according to official statistics.
</P>
<P>
Defense experts hold that Turkey, which owns the second
largest force in the North Atlantic Treaty Organization, should
raise the proportion of the home-made weapons in its military
equipment by expanding financial input for the domestic defense
industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
