<DOCNO> XIE19970922.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-21 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudanese Government, Rebel Faction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The Sudanese government and
and the third largest rebel faction of the southern Sudanese rebel
movement have reached a peace agreement, the Sudan news agency
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached with the People's Liberation Movement
of the Sudan (United Faction) led by Lam Akol, in the town of
Fashuda, southern Sudanese Upper Nile Province, Saturday after
three days of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The agreement ensures the legal status of the Akol faction
during the four-year transition period which will begin as soon as
the constitutional organs in southern Sudan are formed, according
to the official Sudanese newspaper "Al Akhbar" today.
</P>
<P>
Such agreements were also reached with four or five other rebel
factions. They stipulate the right of each faction in southern
Sudan to express its views and prepare for the plebiscite which is
due to take place by the end of the transition period on unity or
secession.
</P>
<P>
Returning to Khartoum today, the head of the Sudanese
government delegation Dayak Mashar who is also the chairman of the
Coordination Council of the Southern States, has disclosed that
Akol will visit Khartoum in a week's time.
</P>
<P>
The Akol faction which belongs to the Shuluk tribe ranks third
in the rebel movement as far as member numbers are concerned.
</P>
<P>
The second place is that of Rayak Mashar faction which belongs
to the Nouer tribe. The John Garang faction of the Dinka tribe
ranks first and is in fact the principal one in southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The Garang movement has persistently refused to negotiate with
the Sudanese government, but it has recently announced its
intention to joint a peace meeting due to convene in Nairobi
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is to be attended by the region's foreign
ministers, to pursue the efforts to end the civil war in southern
Sudan which erupted in 1983 over the ethnic and religious issues
between the north and the south in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese government has welcomed the participation of the
Akol group in the peace process. Speaking to newsmen upon his
return to Khartoum, Ali Haj Mohamed, Sudanese Minister of Federal
Agency and member of the government negotiating team, hailed the
agreement with Akol, attributing the success to the mediation
efforts of the Shuluk tribe spiritual leader between the
government and Akol parties.
</P>
<P>
Akol had joined the Garang-led People's Liberation Movement of
the Sudan in 1986, but seceded in the early 90s on account of
differences with Garang. He then formed the "United Faction".
</P>
<P>
Several months ago, he announced his alliance with Abdul Aziz
Khalid, leader of the northern Sudanese armed opposition. Later
he issued a unilateral declaration proclaiming ceasefire against
the Sudanese government armed forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970922.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Vows to Block Delivery of Missiles to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Turkish top military officer
said here today that Turkey will use all necessary means to block
the transfer of Russian-made missiles to the Cypriot government.
</P>
<P>
"We will evaluate the issue politically, militarily and
internationally. We will do what our interest requires." Ismial
Hakki Karadayi, Chief of General Staff of the Turkish Armed
Forces, told the press at the Ankara airport upon returning from
visits to Belgium, Canada and the United States.
</P>
<P>
He said the missiles have constituted a serious threat to
Turkey's state interests and that Turkey will not remain
indifferent to it.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus signed with Russia an agreement in January to buy
hundreds of anti-aircraft missiles.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish government repeatedly accused the Cypriot
government of endangering its state interests by buying the
missiles. But Cyprus argued that the missiles are for defense,
not directed against any country.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus was divided into two communities of Greek Cypriot and
Turkish Cypriot in 1974 when Turkey landed its troops on the
eastern Mediterranean Sea and took over the northern third
following a failed coup by Greek Cypriots seeking union with
Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared in 1983 a breakaway "Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus" which is recognized only by Turkey.
</P>
</TEXT>
