<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan On ongoing Work and Challenges of UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan today expressed optimism about the overall state of the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the 52nd session of the General Assembly, the U.N.
chief said, "The past year's progress includes the adoption of the
agenda for development, expressing a new consensus to guide our
activities in this critically important field."
</P>
<P>
It included major achievements in disarmament, particularly the
Comprehensive Nuclear-Test-Ban Treaty, the Chemical Weapons
Convention, and the Ottawa process to ban anti-personnel
landmines, he added.
</P>
<P>
In the area of peacekeeping, Annan said, "Significant movement
is taking place among a group of countries towards forming a
standby high readiness brigade within the framework of the United
Nations."
</P>
<P>
"Responding to ever-more frequent requests from member states,
we have expanded our programs in support of good governance,
democratization and strengthening national capacity to promote
human rights," said the secretary-general.
</P>
<P>
Acknowledging the disappointments, Annan said, "The benefits of
economic globalization remain too concentrated to profit the vast
majority of developing countries, enen as official development
assistance continues to decline."
</P>
<P>
"The achievements in disarmaments do not yet encompass the
remaining nuclear stockpiles. Nor have they combined the
proliferation of light weapons and small arms," said Annan.
</P>
<P>
"In a growing number of conflicts, civilian population have
become the explicit targets of factional combatants, and
humanitarian missions have been impeded," added Annan.
</P>
<P>
Annan stressed that violence against women had become the most
pervasive human rights violation, respecting no distinction of
geography, culture or wealth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
