<HEADLINE> Annan Emphasizes Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Secretary-General of
the United Nations Kofi Annan today called on U.N. member states
to make the U.N. General Assembly a "reform assembly."
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 52nd session of the General Assembly here this
morning, he urged member states to "move expeditiously to consider
the package of reforms" that he put forth on July 16.
</P>
<P>
The package gives priority to U.N. institutional
simplification, personnel cutdown and development assistance.
</P>
<P>
Annan said his reform scheme is to meet U.N. objectives "by
promoting at all times the particular needs of the most
disadvantaged societies through the creation of the U.N.
Development Group, a new Office of Development Financing, a new
system of multi-year pledges for development cooperation."
</P>
<P>
He said his reform proposal also includes the strengthening of
the role of the Economic and Social Council, especially in the
area of the macroeconomic policy dialogue.
</P>
<P>
He said he hopes that member states will reach political
consensus before this session ends in mid-December and start
implementation of the reform measures soon after.
</P>
<P>
He also called on them to pay their U.N. assessments "in full,
on time and without condition." 
</P>
</TEXT>
