<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Kazakhstan, China to Upgrade Friendly Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA-ATA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Since they established
diplomatic ties in 1992, relations between China and Kazakhstan
have developed steadily on the basis of their traditional
friendship, thus greatly promoting their cooperation in politics,
economy and culture.
</P>
<P>
China and Kazakhstan have exchanged frequent high-level visits
and agreed that their relations geared toward the 21st century
should be developed on the basis of mutual respect for sovereignty
and territorial integrity and non-interference in each other's
internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan is now expecting the second visit to the country by
Chinese Premier Li Peng which will further upgrade their bilateral
ties.
</P>
<P>
Li first visited Kazakhstan in 1994 and signed an agreement on
the Sino-Kazakh border. Kazakh President Nursultan Nazarbayev paid
visits to China in 1993 and 1995, which led to joint statements on
strengthening and deepening friendly relations between China and
Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, China offered Kazakhstan nuclear security guarantee,
which was considered by the Kazakh side the most powerful proof of
Sino-Kazakh friendship.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also contributed to an agreement on the
reduction of military forces along their border in April 1997 and
an agreement on strengthening trust in the military field in April
1996, by China, Russia, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan and Tajikistan.
</P>
<P>
In July 1996, Chinese President Jiang Zemin's successful visit
to Kazakhstan opened a new page in Sino-Kazakh relations geared
toward the 21st century. The presidents of the two nations issued
a joint declaration, reaffirming the importance of improving
bilateral ties based on the five principles of peaceful
co-existence.
</P>
<P>
China and Kazakhstan, which share more than
1,700-kilometer-long common border, are highly complementary in
their economies and have great potential in economic and trade
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
In June, China National Petroleum Corporation (CNPC) obtained
60 percent shares of Aktobemunajgaz, a major Kazakh oil and gas
company.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Chinese government highly praises Kazakhstan for
its commitment to the "one China" policy and considers this stand
an important base for the smooth development of its relations
with Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
The Kazakh government has said it opposes any activities that
attempt to split China and will not have ties with Taiwan in any
form in support of the cause of the Chinese reunification.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
