<HEADLINE> Swedish Prime Minister Visits NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Swedish Prime Minister Goran
Persson today hinted that his country still wants to stay outside
the North Atlantic alliance for a while.
</P>
<P>
After talks with NATO Secretary General Javier Solana in a
closed session, the Swedish prime minister told the press that
each country has its own right to decide its destiny.
</P>
<P>
But it is important for an outsider to have close talks with
NATO, said Persson whose NATO visit has been postponed due to
scheduling plans.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said that dialogues between NATO and
non-NATO countries are very important.
</P>
<P>
Sweden, however, has been an active participant in the NATO
Partnership for Peace program which incorporates 28 countries
throughout Europe from outside the alliance.
</P>
<P>
When asked how he sees the possible incorporation of the Baltic
states through further NATO enlargement, Persson said that he does
not perceive a new dividing line drawn between the Baltic states
and Russia.
</P>
<P>
"Both the Baltic states and Russia have had good dialogues with
NATO," said the prime minister who regarded the Baltic region as
one of the most prosperous in Europe due to its rapid economic
development.
</P>
<P>
A prosperous Baltic region will in return boost the Swedish
economy, Persson added.
</P>
<P>
NATO chief Solana spoke highly of Sweden's role in the NATO-led
Stabilization Force (SFOR) in Bosnia during his meeting with
Persson. He also briefed the Swedish prime minister about the
latest developments in that country.
</P>
<P>
When asked to comment on Sweden's neutrality by remaining
outside the 15-nation alliance, Solana would not define what
neutrality means nowadays. 
</P>
</TEXT>
