<DOCNO> XIE19970922.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB Report Urges Reform of China's Pension System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 22 (Xinhua) -- China's pension system
faces the long-term problem of a rapidly aging population and the
immediate and urgent problem of funding pensions for employees of
state-owned enterprises, a World Bank report said here today.
</P>
<P>
The report, Old Age Security, one of the bank's China 2020
series, said the number of China's elderly will rise from about 76
million in 1995 to 300 million by 2050.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the ratio of workers to pensioners is
projected to decline from 10 to 1 in 1995 to about 3 to 1 in 2050.
</P>
<P>
Pension outlays are currently funded from current worker
contributions, which, if continued, would place an immense burden on
future generations, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The more immediate and urgent problem is the pension crisis in
the state-owned enterprise sector, which inherited heavy pension
obligations from the central planning era. With the transition to
a market economy, employment in the state enterprise sector is
declining, while the number of pensioners is rising rapidly, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
It charts four essential principles for sustainable reform.
</P>
<P>
-- Firstly, unifying the pension system, bringing together
enterprises and workers currently covered under separate plans
into a single system with common standards.
</P>
<P>
-- Secondly, reducing the pension burden by gradually
increasing the retirement age, lowering the wage replacement rate
and indexing pensions to prices rather than wages.
</P>
<P>
-- Thirdly, introducing funded individual accounts to end the
problems associated with the current pay-as-you-go system.
</P>
<P>
-- And fourthly, ensuring an adequate real rate of return on
pension funds.
</P>
<P>
The report further recommends that the unified pension system
include both mandatory funded individual accounts and a social
insurance scheme.
</P>
<P>
China today has a golden opportunity to move toward a
sustainable, unified pension system that combines a defined
benefit basic public pillar with funded individual accounts, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Although the reforms do carry transition costs, China's such
costs are lower while its capacity to bear these costs is higher
than in other countries that have made similar transitions, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
There are four factors behind it -- the benefits to be reaped
from unification of the pension system, rapid economic growth,
structural change in the economy, and expected capital gains.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970922.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Nationwide Campaign to Study Party Congress Documents (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese across the country
are saying that a stronger, improved Party leadership is the key
to building socialism with Chinese characteristics.
</P>
<P>
Comments like these have been heard during a nationwide
campaign to study the documents of the 15th National Congress of
the Communist Party of China (CPC), which ended last week.
</P>
<P>
To lead China into the 21st century, an effort must be also
made in promoting cultural and ethical progress, in consolidating
the Party and in strengthening unity among China's various ethnic
groups, and in maintaining political stability, people say.
</P>
<P>
The report delivered by General Secretary Jiang Zemin at the
Congress has gotten enthusiastic response from intellectuals like
Prof. Li Chonghuai of Wuhan University, who says, "It is essential
that the Party's nature as the vanguard and its purity be
maintained and its solidarity and fighting power increased to
continue China's modernization drive into the next century."
</P>
<P>
Jiang Zemin said that the Party's sole purpose is to serve the
people wholeheartedly and that an effort should be made to open
more channels for democracy. "This is especially important for
Party work at the grassroots level in rural areas," said Li
Zunying, Party secretary of Xintang county in Hebei province.
</P>
<P>
Some people, lured by the prospect of material benefits, have
departed from the basic moral standards, and this deterioration is
having an important influence in causing corruption in society.
</P>
<P>
"It is encouraging that the report emphasized building a
socialist culture with Chinese characteristics, and making a new
effort to improve cultural and ethical progress," said Shu Yi, a
member of the Beijing Municipal Committee of the Chinese People's
Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC).
</P>
</TEXT>
