<DOCNO> XIE19970922.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 14:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti, Bahraini Stock Markets Move Towards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait Stock Exchange
today started showing live daily trading deals in the Bahraini
bourse via special devices in a step towards the all-round linkage
of the two markets.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti bourse Director General Hisham Al-Otaibi said the
measure is aimed at getting Kuwaiti investors acquainted
themselves with the daily developments in Bahraini stock market
ahead of the linkage of the two bourses.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait announced Sunday the stock exchanges in the two Gulf
countries will sign an agreement Saturday to open the way for
cross trading between the two markets.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, expected to become effective early next year,
aims to link clearing houses and brokerage firms of the two
markets that will ease the way for cross trading.
</P>
<P>
A clearing house or similar body is also expected to be built
in Bahrain that will play the same role as the Kuwait Clearing
Company which guarantees share transactions here.
</P>
<P>
The agreement would be the second of its kind among stock
markets of the Gulf Cooperation Council's (GCC) states. GCC
groups Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, the United Arab Emirates, Oman,
Qatar and Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
Oman and Bahrain have already linked their floors and a
number of companies from the two countries have been listed in
both exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Exchange officials believe that the joining together of the
Kuwaiti and Bahraini markets would encourage cross-listing of
companies and the flow of capital between the two countries, thus
boosting the economic cooperation among them.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait stock exchange has been performing well since last
year and so far more than 70 companies have been listed on the
market.
</P>
<P>
On January 6, the stock exchange markets of Kuwait, Egypt and
Lebanon were linked together via a computer network displaying
daily deals in each country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970922.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Krajicek Pulls out of Grand Slam Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, Septtember 22 (Xinhua) -- Former Wimbledon champion
Richard Krajicek pulled out of the 6-million-dollar Grand Slam Cup
on Monday, opening the way for Australian Mark Woodforde to join
the field at the elite 16-man event which opens in Munich Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Officials said the Dutchman withdrew with an Achilles tendon
problem which has plagued him since the summer.
</P>
<P>
Woodforde moved into Krajicek's Tuesday first-round match
against Chile's Marcelo Rios, flying in from India after a Davis
Cup loss.
</P>
<P>
Swede Magnus Norman assumed the next replacement spot after
both South African Wayne Ferreira and Briton Tim Henman declined
it.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere on the injury front, Frenchman Cedric Pioline
confirmed to officials that he will be ready to compete at the
event, which brings together the top performers at the four Grand
Slams.
</P>
<P>
The Wimbledon finalist was unable to complete his opening
singles in France's Davis Cup relegation round tie against Belgium
on Friday, quitting in the fourth set with a knee problem against
Johan Van Herck.
</P>
<P>
He did not play the reverse singles on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Pioline is set for an opening match against Filip Dewulf, a
replay of the French-Belgian Davis Cup hostilities which the
Belgians won at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Britain's U.S. Open finalist Greg Rusedski was one of the few
entries with just a quick commute to reach Munich after resting
last week.
</P>
<P>
The New York losing finalist plays a Tuesday first-round
contest against Australia's Todd Woodbridge in the rich knockout
competition, being held in September for the first time in its
eight-year history after moving from a December date.
</P>
<P>
Also Tuesday, former French Open champion Yevgeny Kafelnikov
takes on Spain's Sergi Bruguera, who earned his place in the field
by reaching the French Open final.
</P>
<P>
Rusedski qualified by becoming the first British man to make
the top ten after his New York showing and after gaining a
semi-final place a week later in Britain on clay.
</P>
<P>
World No. 1 Pete Sampras and U.S. Open titleholder Patrick
Rafter were expected in Munich Monday after a flight from the
United States, where Sampras clinched a 4-1 Davis Cup final place
for his country against Sweden with a reverse singles win against
the Aussie.
</P>
<P>
Both men have a day off Tuesday, with Sampras playing Spain's
Felix Mantilla and Rafter opening against former world No. 1
Austrian Thomas Muster, all on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The tournament is an undisguised payday for the game's elite. A
first-round loser can get 100,000 dollars, while losing in the
final is worth a consoling 750,000.
</P>
<P>
Sampras, who took the title in the inaugural year of 1990, has
claimed more than five million dollars in prize money from this
event alone, competing in five editions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
