<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia-U.S. Commission Session Opens in Moscow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The Russia-U.S. Commission for
Economic and Technological Cooperation opened its 9th session here
today, the Itar-Tass News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Opening the session of the so-called Chernomyrdin-Gore
commission, Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin said the
"monumental task" for the commission is the implementation of the
Helsinki economic initiative launched by Russian and
U.S. presidents Boris Yeltsin and Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the Helsinki initiative "outlines the landmarks
for bilateral cooperations on the way to the 21st century."
</P>
<P>
These landmarks, he said, mainly include lifting the remaining
trade and investment barriers; building a mechanism to ensure fair
access to the markets; furthering Russia's integration into the
world economy, including Russia's entry into the World Trade
Organization and others.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin noted that "attaining these objectives will mean
substantial support for Russian reform."
</P>
<P>
In his speech, visiting U.S. Vice President Albert Gore
expressed satisfaction with the developments in both
Russian-U.S. relations and Russia's integration into the world
economy since the commission's previous meetings in Washington and
Chicago last February.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin and Gore, co-chairmen of the commission also
agreed to proceed with the joint program of space exploration
aboard the Russian space station Mir.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Vice President arrived in Moscow on Sunday for three
days of talks, with the focus on cooperation in space, economy and
nuclear non-proliferation between the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
