<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Give Chernobyl Victims 1.1 Million Dollars Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)
today granted one million ECU (1.1 million U.S. dollars) in aid to
the victims of the Chernobyl nuclear disaster, totaling its
Chernobyl aid to 8.14 million ECU (8.21 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The European Commission (EC), the executive body of the
15-nation EU, entrusted the European Community Humanitarian Office
with the aid, which would support programs to help radiation
victims in Ukraine, Belarus and Russia for nine months.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 100,000 people fell victims to the radioactive
fallout after the 1986 disaster at the Chernobyl nuclear power
plant in the former Soviet Union, now near the border between
Belarus and Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
The International Red Cross and two non-governmental
organizations from Germany and Italy will use the fund to treat
the victims and deliver necessary nutrition food in the countries.
</P>
<P>
The Red Cross is to continue a program of screening children
for thyroid cancers and screening food and water in highly
polluted areas of radiation, and introduce a psycho-social program
for people.
</P>
<P>
The aid will enable an Italian non-governmental organization to
continue work with the main local hospital in Kiev, Ukraine, to
treat thyroid cancer sufferers.
</P>
<P>
The aid will also help the humanitarian work of a German
organization which has been supporting a local children's surgery
center since 1991 in Minsk, Belarus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970922.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Mayor to Be Awarded Habitat Scroll of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Center
for Human Settlements (Habitat) has announced that Chinese Mayor
Huang Ziqiang of Zhongshan Municipality had been named as one of
six recipients of an international award, the Habitat Scroll of
Honor.
</P>
<P>
A press release reaching here today said Mayor Huang Ziqiang
would be awarded for "his outstanding role in the sustainable
development and management of human settlements in Zhongshan
Municipality".
</P>
<P>
He has spearheaded the Municipality's efforts in improving the
living and ecological environment of the city and to upgrade
urban infrastructure, it added.
</P>
<P>
The Zhongshan Municipality in south China's Guangdong
province, has implemented 98 low-profit housing projects during
the past several years, offering 51,300 apartments to
shelter-needy citizens.
</P>
<P>
The other recipients are Senator Oscar Lopez Velarde Vega of
Mexico, Mother Center Stuttgart-West of Germany, South African
Homeless People's Federation, Richard Goethert of the United
States and Nabeel Hamdi of the United Kingdom, and Federation of
Canadian Municipalities of Canada.
</P>
<P>
The awards are scheduled to be presented on October 6, the
World Habitat Day, in Bonn, Germany, by Dr. Wally N'Dow,
Assistant Secretary-General of the Habitat.
</P>
<P>
The annual award is presented to organizations or individuals
for their outstanding contribution to human settlements
development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
