<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank/IMF Development Committee Meeting Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The Development Committee
of the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund (IMF) ended
its 56th meeting here today after reaching agreement on a number
of pressing issues, according to a communique.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice Premier Zhu Rongji, World Bank President James
Wolfensohn and IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus addressed
the four-hour plenary session. Speakers also included a number of
government ministers and chief bankers.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the meeting agreed that corruption and weak
governance undermine macro-economic stability, private sector
activity and sustainable development objectives, and may erode
international support for development cooperation.
</P>
<P>
They emphasized that corruption is a global problem that
requires complementary actions by all countries, said the
communique issued after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
While stressing that member governments shoulder the primary
responsibility for combating corruption and strengthening
governance, the participants welcomed the more active involvement
of the World Bank and the IMF, each within their respective
mandate, in responding to member governments' requests to
strengthen their institutions and performance in these areas, the
communique added.
</P>
<P>
The ministerial-level committee, the only
broadly-representative group of key policy makers under the World
Bank and the IMF, focuses specially on developing country issues
and fosters resolution of critical problems for the mutual benefit
 of all countries.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, the participants reiterated their support for
Multilateral Investment Guarantee Agency's (MIGA) continued growth
 in response to the expanding demand for its services, the
communique said.
</P>
<P>
They also welcomed the World Bank Group Action Program designed
 to strengthen the Group's ability to increase private
participation in infrastructure in the context of its overall
objectives to support poverty reduction and sustainable
development, and stressed the importance of coordination in the
Group based on agreed country frameworks and strategies.
</P>
<P>
The Implementation of the Debt Initiative for Heavily Indebted
Poor Countries (HIPC) was another topic at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The ministers welcomed the progress in implementing the Debt
Initiative to support governments that show strong commitment to
reform, and encouraged eligible countries to undertake the policy
actions necessary to put them on the path to securing debt relief,
 the communique noted.
</P>
<P>
They also noted the importance of macroeconomic stability in
strengthening the financial systems of developing countries, as
recent events including the financial crisis in Southeast Asia
have shown, and viewed enhanced cooperation between the World Bank
 and the IMF as "an urgent priority."
</P>
<P>
The participants also praised the recent agreement guiding
increased collaboration to help member countries strengthen their
financial systems, said Driss Jettou, chairman of the committee
and finance minister of Morocco.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that the ministers expressed their deep
appreciation for the warm hospitality provided by the Chinese
government and the Hong Kong Monetary Authority, and decided that
the committee's next meeting will be held on April 17, 1998 in
Washington, the United States.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
