<HEADLINE> Israeli Embassy Sealed Off after Shooting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 22 (Xinhua) - Jordanian police stepped up
security around the Israeli embassy here after two Israeli
security guards were lightly wounded by a gunman outside Israeli
ambassador's residence about three kilometers away.
</P>
<P>
The streets near the embassy were blocked off and this would
remain until tomorrow morning, a patrolling police officer who
refused to be named told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Although the shooting took place near the ambassador's
residence, which was the former Israeli embassy, Jordanian police
still decided to tighten security around the embassy in case of
new violence, the officer said.
</P>
<P>
At about 7:30 local time (04:30 GMT) this morning, a man on a
vehicle passing by the ambassador's residence took out a gun and
shot at the security guards of the residence who were on routine
inspection duty.
</P>
<P>
Altogether four guards were lightly wounded, two of them were
Israelis and the other Jordanians, according to Jordanian Minister
of State for Information Affairs Samir Mutawe.
</P>
<P>
The attacker fled the scene. Jordanian police traced the vehicle
only to find the empty van near the U.S. embassy here at the sixth
circle, not far from the Israeli embassy, the police said.
</P>
<P>
Mutawe condemned the incident as an act of terrorism. No one
has claimed responsibility.
</P>
<P>
Israeli embassy spokesman Roey Gilad, told the press that the
two wounded Israeli diplomats received preliminary medical care in
Amman and then were transferred back to Israel for further
hospitalization.
</P>
<P>
Jordan signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1994 despite
strong domestic opposition.
</P>
<P>
The majority of the Jordanians are of Palestinian origin, and
the shooting came at a time of heightened tension between
Palestinians and Israelis as the Mideast peace process remain
deadlocked.
</P>
<P>
In July, a Jordanian soldier was sentenced to life in prison
for shooting to death seven Israeli schoolgirls and wounding seven
others on March 13 near the border with Israel.
</P>
<P>
The sentence, regarded as unjust by some Jordanians, triggered
demonstrations in both Amman and the soldier's home town. 
</P>
</TEXT>
