<HEADLINE> Giant Panda Dies of Kidney Failure in Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Huan Huan, a gift female giant
panda from China died of anemia and kidney failure in Tokyo's Ueno
Zoo today, at about 25.
</P>
<P>
China presented Huan Huan to Japan in 1980, that gave birth to
three cubs, with two of them, namely Chu Chu and Tong Tong, still
survive.
</P>
<P>
After settling down in the Ueno Zoo 17 years ago, Huan Huan has
brought great enjoyments to tourists, children in particular.
</P>
<P>
Upon learning her death over television, many children fell in
deep sorrow. The zoo has decided to hold mourning activities for
loving Huan Huan on September 23 and accept flowers from mourning
children at the same time.
</P>
<P>
As the sole female giant panda ever to have given birth in
Japan, Huan Huan was presented to the country after Lan Lan died
in 1979. Lan Lan had been given to Japan in 1972 together with Kan
Kan, a male panda, in commemoration of the normalization of
diplomatic relations between the two nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
