<DOCNO> XIE19970922.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: Africa Attracts More Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Foreign direct
investment inflows into Africa reached 4,949 million U.S. Dollars
in 1996, 5.3 percent more than that of 1995, said The World
Investment Report 1997 released by the United Nations Conference
on Trade and Development.
</P>
<P>
This indicates that the African continent, which is under
economic recovering, is attracting more foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
According to analysis made by the report, there are five
characteristics in the foreign investment inflows into Africa.
</P>
<P>
Firstly, the share of north Africa in Africa's total inflows
has declined from an average of 44 percent during 1986-1990 to 38
percent during 1991-1996.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, the corresponding share of sub-Saharan Africa has
risen slightly from 56 percent to 62 percent within the two
periods.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, investment flows into Africa have become less
concentrated. The five largest recipients during 1991-1996 --
Nigeria, Egypt, Morocco, Tunisia and Angola -- accounted for 78
percent of all investment inflows to the region. But the
corresponding share during 1981-1985 of the top five recipients
--Egypt, Nigeria, Tunisia, Cameroun and Angola -- was 93 percent.
</P>
<P>
Fourthly, the share of investment for oil exports in Africa's
total inflows has increased marginally, from 71 percent during
1986-1990 to 73 percent during 1991-1996.
</P>
<P>
Fifthly, the share of Africa's investment inflows accounted
for by the least developed countries in the region has remained
almost the same, an average of 18 percent during 1986-1990 and an
average of 17 percent during 1991-1996.
</P>
<P>
The investment made by developing countries in Africa is
declining by more than a half, from 11 percent during 1986-1990
to 5 percent during 1991-1996, although foreign direct investment
inflows into the continent increased during the past decades.
</P>
<P>
Of course, the absolute level of foreign direct investment
flows into Africa is increasing, from an annual average of 800
million U.S. Dollars during 1975-1980 to 3.9 billion Dollars
during 1990-1996. Although rising from a low level, foreign
direct investment inflows into Africa grew by fivefold between
the periods 1975-1980 and 1990-1996, compared with 4.7 times for
Latin America and sevenfold for developed countries as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Foreign direct investment has played a significant role in
Africa's economic rehabilitation and development. Africa's
foreign direct investment stock was 13 percent of the region's
Gross Domestic Product (GDP) in 1995. If only sub-Saharan Africa
is considered, the share is as much as 17 percent, compared to
about 13 percent for western Europe, 14 percent for Asia, and 18
percent for Latin America and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
In relation to gross fixed capital formation during 1990-1995,
foreign direct investment flows to Africa accounted for 5.4
percent, compared with nearly 5.5 percent for Asia, 8.4 percent
for Latin America and the Caribbean and 5.9 percent for western
Europe. There are a number of countries in Africa which by this
measure, received more foreign direct investment than major
developing countries in Asia and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
It is noteworthy that although western industrialized
countries are main sources of foreign direct investment flows to
Africa, Asia's developing countries have become important
investors for Africa.
</P>
<P>
It is important that a number of firms from Africa are
themselves beginning to become outward investors. Although these
firms remain relatively rare and small in size with an outward
foreign direct investment stock of 26 billion U.S. Dollars in
1996, it shows that there are firms in Africa that can be
competitive internationally, not only through trade but also
through production in foreign markets.
</P>
<P>
Now, international community believes that the prospect of
improvements in foreign direct investment in Africa is bright.
First, there is a favourable economic growth performance in the
region. Africa's economic recovery, which started in 1994, was
strong in 1996, with domestic output rising by 4.4 percent, the
greatest increase since 1988. This performance compares
favorably with the 2.7 percent GDP increase in 1995, and
represents a turn-round in the per-capita income growth rate.
</P>
<P>
Second, foreign direct investment and trade liberalization in
African countries. In an effort to improve their investment
regimes, several countries in Africa have removed ownership
restrictions, reduced taxation rates and abolished price
controls. As of January 1, 1997, some 45 African developing
countries had concluded at least one bilateral investment treaty
and in total, had signed 267 bilateral investment treaties, of
which 17 were with countries in the continent.
</P>
<P>
Third, privatization in Africa. Sub-Saharan African countries
continued to sell off state-owned enterprises to foreign
investors. They raised 544 million U.S. Dollars in 1995, compared
with only 74 million in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Lastly, regional integration agreements and links with other
region. The convergence of economic policies in many African
economies is improving prospects for enhanced regional
cooperation. Governments are harmonizing their investment codes
and customs duties. Meanwhile, African countries are
strengthening their links with other regions.
</P>
<P>
Overall, prospects for an improved foreign direct investment
during the second half of the 1990s appear favourable. For
example, oil and mining companies have announced investment plans
for Africa in 1997 which total some 5 billion U.S. Dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
