<HEADLINE> Landslide Renders 4,000 Homeless in South Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- At least 4,000 people in south
Nigeria's Anambra state have been rendered homeless following the
collapse of 200 buildings ravaged by gully erosion, the Daily
Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
Some of the homeless now sleep on verandas and in market
stalls, said Igwe Joe Nwakobi, traditional of Obosi town hit by
the landslide.
</P>
<P>
According to him, there was the likelihood of more houses
giving way to the natural disaster before the end of the current
rainy season, which extends from April to October.
</P>
<P>
Nwakobi said that all kinds of local control measures such as
planting of grasses, digging of water trenches and lining the
water course with sand bags had not helped much. 
</P>
</TEXT>
