<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng: China to Maintain Long-term Cooperation with WB, IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng
said here today that the Chinese government wishes to maintain
long-term and stable cooperative relations with the World Bank
(WB) and the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
Li made the remark at a banquet given here in honor of the
finance ministers and central bank governors who are here to
attend the annual meetings of the World Bank Group and the IMF
which will open tomorrow, as well as their spouses.
</P>
<P>
He said that since 1980 China has been enjoying close
cooperation with the WB and IMF, which have provided helpful
assistance to China's economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
He said the two monetary bodies meanwhile have increased their
knowledge of China and accumulated some experience in conducting
cooperation with member states, especially developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The fact that the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HK
SAR) of China has been chosen as the venue for this year's WB/IMF
annual meetings "demonstrates that the international community
values Hong Kong as an international financial center and
testifies to their good-will in enhancing their cooperation with
China and their great trust in the HK SAR headed by Mr. Tung Chee
Hwa," Li said.
</P>
<P>
The premier noted that the recent 15th National Congress of the
Chinese Communist Party identified the Deng Xiaoping Theory as the
guiding ideology for China, elected the central collective
leadership with President Jiang Zemin at the core and drew up a
cross-century program for China's modernization drive.
</P>
<P>
"We will stick to and develop our all-directional,
multi-layered and cross-sector opening-up pattern, and maintain a
sustained, rapid and healthy economic growth, which will afford us
more opportunities for cooperation with other countries," Li said.
</P>
<P>
At present, he went on, the trend towards multipolarity is
gaining momentum. Great changes have taken place in the
international economic and financial arena, he added.
</P>
<P>
All these developments have presented both opportunities and
challenges to the WB and IMF, Li stated.
</P>
<P>
"It is both our hope and belief that the two institutions will
be able to adapt to the changing situation, look into the 21st
century, and give more consideration to the interests and needs of
the developing countries in the overall interests of world peace
and development," he said.
</P>
<P>
The two bodies will "give full play to their respective
advantages and make fresh contribution to regional and global
economic development in the spirit of mutual respect, equal
treatment, mutual benefit, reciprocity and seeking common ground
while reserving differences," the premier said.
</P>
<P>
Li concluded his speech by wishing the annual meetings a
"complete success."
</P>
<P>
Nearly 500 guests attended the banquet including WB/IMF Annual
Meetings Chairman Mohammed K. Khirbash, WB President James
Wolfensohn, IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus, and Chairman
of the Group of 24 Ministers Antonio Casas Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
HK SAR Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa and his wife Betty Tung,
and principal officials of the HK SAR government were also present.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-Premier Zhu Rongji was also present.
</P>
<P>
Premier Li Peng will deliver a speech at the opening ceremony
of the WB/IMF annual meetings tomorrow morning.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
