<DOCNO> XIE19970922.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Army Exchange Heavy Fire with S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, September 22 (Xinhua) -- State radio and television
in Sierra Leone reported that shells fired from a Nigerian alpha
jet on Saturday evening have caused structural damage to the main
building of the Electricity Power House in the capital.
</P>
<P>
Shells also destroyed a nearby police hospital, putting both
staff and about 100 patients to flight, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
State radio reported that no one was killed in the attacks but
Senior Electrical Engineer Yembeh Mansaray sustained serious
injuries on the face.
</P>
<P>
"We are appalled over what has turned out to be reckless
bombings of selected targets by the Nigerian air force," Hassan
Barrie, under secretary for energy and power, told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Damage to the building was put at 100,000 U.S. Dollars. A
Lebanese resident near the power house said he was using
binoculars when he saw the jet "coming at full speed as if it
intends to crash on the building."
</P>
<P>
"It was actually targeting an oil tug which was anchored at
the power house jetty. It is apparent they suspected the tug,''
he added.
</P>
<P>
Officials said the tug has been lying idle at the jetty for
two months now because of the blockade imposed by west African
leaders in their summit in Abuja, Nigeria last month. The
leaders aimed to force the military regime to return power back
to the civilian government.
</P>
<P>
"We were only enforcing the blockade and sending a warning to
would-be violators that we shall not hesitate to destroy any boat
or vessel attempting to ignore the embargo," a Nigerian captain
based at Jui, 13 miles east of the capital Freetown told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, heavy fire were traded between Nigerian troops
occupying Sierra Leone's international airport and soldiers of
the Sierra Leone army early today, residents in the area told
Xinhua in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
The airport is located 10 miles from the Sierra Leone River
and is accessible by ferry.
</P>
<P>
One resident said both sides began shooting at each other at
about 8 am local time, initially with small arms fire before
resorting to a series of bombardment.
</P>
<P>
Both sides blamed the other for the fighting in which each
side said they suffered "only slight injuries."
</P>
<P>
A Nigerian colonel at the airport reached by telephone said,
"We have been harassed since Saturday by rebels linked with the
Sierra Leone army. We have to defend ourselves when we are
attacked so this is why we fired back this morning."
</P>
<P>
Military sources in Freetown disputed the account saying, "a
group of Nigerian soldiers were moving from their positions
towards the area where the Sierra Leone army is based. We asked
them to halt but they ignored the warning. So we fired warning
shots."
</P>
<P>
The bombing caused slight panic in the capital but calm
returned by 8.45 am.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, two multinational companies resumed operations
today, three months after the May 25 military coup.
</P>
<P>
Ivan Varroll, manager of Sierra Leone Brewery, a subsidiary of
Heineken of Holland and Guiness of Scotland, told Xinhua, "We are
working on limited production until we repair our damaged
machines and bring in additional raw materials."
</P>
<P>
The brewery suffered extensive damage to its bottling plant
and laboratory after the coup.
</P>
<P>
Workers of the other company, the American-run Seaboard Flour
Mill, turned up in "full force" today to start production.
</P>
<P>
"The mill has enough raw materials to produce flour for the
next six months," said head miller John Williams.
</P>
<P>
Observers said the resumption of production means the size of
a loaf of bread, which had shrinked considerably over the past
months, will be increased. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
