<DOCNO> XIE19970922.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China on Road to Build New Social Security System  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Health care and pension
systems in China have been restructured in recent years, but there
is still a long way to go to set up a new social security system
which can meet the demand of a market economy.
</P>
<P>
Guo Shuqing, secretary general of the State Commission for
Restructuring Economic Systems, made the remark here today at a
seminar on "Household Security in China: Health and Pensions",
part of a series of China-focused seminars organized by the World
Bank today.
</P>
<P>
The health status of the Chinese people has reached a
remarkably high level compared with many other developing
countries, with life expectancy at birth standing at about 70
years, Guo said.
</P>
<P>
But the old mechanism of providing medical care is facing great
challenges: the cost has increased much faster than the national
income growth and, at the same time, the efficiency has gone down,
the Chinese official said.
</P>
<P>
The key point of the old medical care system in urban areas, is
that state-owned enterprises or governmental institutions covered
all expenses of their employees, and the government covered all
expenses of these public units.
</P>
<P>
While in rural areas, a collectively-owned cooperative medical
care system paid for their members as much as possible, Guo told
the seminar.
</P>
<P>
With the advance of market-oriented economic reform, the
government has become much less responsible for the health care
system of the enterprises while the cooperative medical care
system has collapsed in many villages, he said.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, the State Council, China's cabinet, has selected
several pilot cities to conduct health care reform experiments,
establishing a city-based medical care system, with both employees
 and employers contributing to it, Guo said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970922.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Help Indonesia Extinguish Forest Fires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto
has accepted Malaysia's offer to dispatch 1,500 firefighters to
help the country put out forest fires that have been raging in the
islands of Sumatra and Kalimantan, a senior official said here
today.
</P>
<P>
"Some 1,210 of them are for Sumatra," Coordinating Minister for
People's Welfare Azwar Anas said after meeting with Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the 1,210 firefighters for Sumatra, Malaysia has
also offered to send paramedics and military officers, Azwar said.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the neighboring country also
prepared three Hercules C-130 aircraft for cloud seeding, which
will come from Malaysia's airports in Subang, Labahan and Sabah.
</P>
<P>
At least 300,000 hectares of forest, mostly in Sumatra and
Kalimantan, have been destroyed by fire in Indonesia this year.
</P>
<P>
The haze caused by fires has reached an unhealthy level here,
Malaysia and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Officials here said that about 20 million people are in danger
of respiratory problems due to the thick smoke.
</P>
<P>
The haze has also caused the delay of 800 flights and at least
seven boat collisions on Central Kalimantan's Mahakam River in the
last few months.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the Indonesian government ordered 176 plantation
firms, which accused of using fire for land clearing, to stop
firing forest within 15 days.  
</P>
</TEXT>
