<DOCNO> XIE19970922.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB Publishes Report on Financing Health Care in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 22 (Xinhua) -- China's dramatic
improvements in health care have begun eroding but if the country
returns to a policy of vigorous finance and support for public
health, it could meet the needs of present and future generations,
a World Bank report suggests.
</P>
<P>
The report -- Financing Health Care -- which is part of the
China 2020 series prepared at the request of China, explains
policy changes which can remove disparities in coverage, increase
efficiency and ensure public financing to address the demands of a
more affluent and aging population.
</P>
<P>
In 1950, life expectancy in China was less than 40 years; by
1982, it had risen to 69 years. This shift reflects dramatic
improvement in the overall health of China's population, linked to
policies that by 1975 had brought health care to nearly 90 percent
of the population and that contained costs despite the vast gains
in health coverage.
</P>
<P>
Despite its remarkable achievements, China's health care system
today faces deep problems. The gap in access to health care has
grown, particularly between urban and rural areas, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
Inefficiency has grown in China's health services, for example,
by allowing health care providers to offset losses on
government-set prices by permitting them to charge high prices for
drugs and high-tech diagnostic tests, the report said.
</P>
<P>
And health care costs rose by 11 percent a year in real terms
from 1986 to 1993. These costs will continue to rise as China's
income grows and its population ages.
</P>
<P>
The report stresses the need for health spending to target the
poor, and discusses the ways to undo the distortions of pricing
and allocation of health resources that have diminished the
quality and effectiveness of China's health services.
</P>
<P>
The report shows how better control over health-care
investments, and more efficient risk pooling in insurance, can
improve both coverage and quality.
</P>
<P>
To achieve these changes, the report suggests that spending on
strengthened national public health activities should increase as
a share of GDP by 2001.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970922.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China on Road to Build New Social Security System (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In addition, he said, a variety of other health care systems
have developed in recent years, such as serious diseases security
funds, commercial insurance, as well as charities and donations.
</P>
<P>
Turning to pensions, the Chinese official said that after two
years' experiments, urban pension systems have begun to be
unified. Up to now, almost 90 million people in urban areas have
joined the pension system, he said.
</P>
<P>
But the biggest problem is that there was few accumulation for
the aged in their past working years and worse still, an
increasing number of retired people now are paid by the pension
system, he said.
</P>
<P>
There is some 50 billion yuan (six billion US dollars) in the
pension scheme nationwide, but a majority of cities and provinces
have already run into the red, he said.
</P>
<P>
Thus, household security, health and pensions call for a
"two-pillar system" -- basic security established by the
government, and supplementary security through market, he said.
</P>
<P>
"But now, both pillars are not strong enough, therefore
household savings in bank deposits are still increasing so much.
Last year it increased by 885.9 billion yuan (106 billion US
dollars) or 13 percent of the total GDP," Guo said.
</P>
<P>
With the emergence of pensions and diversified medical care
systems, fund management is becoming more and more important to
China's economy, he added.
</P>
<P>
To prevent risks, all the surplus of the social security funds
has been required to be used to buy government bonds since 1994
and this seems to be the best choice at present. But for
supplementary security funds, a commercialized management of
investment is needed, he said.
</P>
<P>
Among those addressing the 90-minute session were David de
Ferranti, director of the Human Development Department at the
World Bank, and Masahiro Yamada, managing director of Nippon Life
Insurance Company.
</P>
<P>
Yamada summarized the latest developments in Japan's social
security system and hoped that Japanese experience in the field
might be helpful to China.
</P>
<P>
Facing a rapidly aging society, Japan is in dire need of social
security, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ferranti commented that what is done to pensions and health
care has large implications not only on household security but
also on a nation's economy.
</P>
<P>
He expressed confidence that China is "well positioned to meet
the challenges" ahead on the road to build a new and efficient
social security system.  
</P>
</TEXT>
