<HEADLINE> S. African Tourism to Double Its Contribution to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 22 (Xinhua) -- South African Tourism
Minister Pallo Jordan has predicted that tourism in the country
could increase its contribution from the present 4.5 percent of
gross domestic product (GDP) to eight percent by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the annual conference of the Airlines Association
of Southern Africa, Jordan said targets set for the next three
years included increasing foreign exchange earnings from tourism
to a rate of 15 percent a year from 2.65 billion U.S. Dollars to
4.88 billion U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's ministry has aimed to raise the number of foreign
visitors to South Africa by an average of 17 percent a year to
2.2 million by 2000, and African visitors by six percent a year
to 4.8 million and domestic holiday makers by 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
This would raise sustainable employment opportunities in the
sector from 550,000 to 860,000, he said.
</P>
<P>
"If we could increase the tourism contribution in the GDP to
10 percent, the industry could generate 40 billion Rand (8.51
billion U.S. Dollars) annually and create two million jobs. No
other industry has such potential," said the minister.
</P>
<P>
A restructured and more effective South African Tourism
Organization would embark on a new marketing drive in the new
year, he added. 
</P>
