<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Road Network to be Managed by Private </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 22 (Xinhua) -- More than 90 percent of
South Africa's road network could be managed by the private
sector in the future, local daily Business Day today quoted
Transport Department Director-General Khetso Gordhan as saying.
</P>
<P>
The South African government wished to move towards the New
Zealand model of greater private sector involvement in the
management of the road network, Gordhan said at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of achieving this was through the national
roads agency, the legislation for which was recently approved by
the cabinet, he said.
</P>
<P>
The new agency would initially manage, construct and maintain
South Africa's 7,000 km national road network, which was likely
to be extended to the 20,000 km of primary roads in the next five
to six years.
</P>
<P>
"Ultimately we would like to set up a holding company for the
national road agency with nine provincial agencies in place as
well," Gordhan noted.
</P>
<P>
The South African Transport Department was planning to make a
major reform, during which about 1,000 of its staff were expected
to be retrenched, said a high-ranking official in the department,
who asked not to be identified.
</P>
<P>
The national roads agency would have a staff of about 150 with
about 30 people in the national head office, the official added.
</P>
</TEXT>
