<HEADLINE> Syria Satisfied With AL Recommendation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq
al-Shara here today expressed satisfaction over the recommendation
by the Arab foreign ministers to freeze further moves towards
normalizing ties with Israel.
</P>
<P>
In a final statement, the two-day 108th Arab League (AL)
ministerial council meeting recommended that AL member states
freeze further moves towards normalizing ties with Israel and
suspend multilateral talks.
</P>
<P>
"Issues related to normalization and multilateral negotiations
should not be raised except after making a basic headway in the
peace drive," he told foreign reporters.
</P>
<P>
The headway must primarily involve issues like Israeli troop
withdrawal from occupied Arab territories, freeze in Jewish
settlement building and achieving peace, according to Shara.
</P>
<P>
Syrian-Israeli peace talks broke down 18 months ago after a
spate of suicide bombings hit Jerusalem. Syria refused to return
to negotiations, accusing the Israelis of not honoring the
commitment of the former government to return the occupied Golan
Heights.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian official also lashed out at views that the decision
on attending the fourth Middle East and North Africa (MENA)
Economic Summit should be left to each individual country.
</P>
<P>
"These words lack accuracy," he said, in a vague reference to
some Arab countries' insistence on convening the regional economic
forum that involves Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Doha summit was not mentioned in the final statement.
</P>
<P>
However, discussions at the Cairo gathering Sunday shows "an
inclination that the convocation of the Doha conference will hinge
on tangible progress to be made on all Mideast peace tracks," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Shara anticipated that only three or four Arab countries would
attend the summit if it is ever convened in the Qatari capital in
November.
</P>
<P>
He further said that the only means through which Israel can
be persuaded to achieve peace is by clinging to a solid Arab
attitude and refusing to offer any concessions.
</P>
<P>
As a direct spinoff of the Mideast peace process, the annual
MENA conference had been held in Casablanca, Amman and Cairo since
1994.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia and Syria flatly rejected the conference that
involves Israel, while Qatar insists on hosting. Egypt had been
saying that its participation hinges on progress on the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Jordan are the only Arab countries that have peace
treaties with Israel, with which Qatar has limited trade ties.
</P>
</TEXT>
