<HEADLINE> East African Coffee Producers to Raise Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Coffee producing countries
in east Africa have agreed to start a series of cooperation
programs aimed at improving bean quality and raising coffee
production, The East African reported today.
</P>
<P>
The weekly newspaper said that at a two-day meeting held
recently in Tanzania, officials from Ethiopia, Kenya, Rwanda,
Tanzania and Uganda pledged to work together to fight coffee
pests, implement breeding programs and coffee quality
improvement.
</P>
<P>
Wilson Opile, a coffee scientist from Kenya told the meeting
that the potential is there in east Africa, adding that "if we
pull the resources together, we can increase production and
quality."
</P>
<P>
For instance, he said, "in Tanzania, they are struggling to
find disease resistant varieties and in Kenya we already have all
the information."
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Ted Lingle, Executive Director of the
Speciality Coffee Association of America, as saying that "if they
(east African coffee nations) get their act together and
cooperate on how to improve husbandry and raise yields, they
could easily double, if not quadruple the total output."
</P>
<P>
Leading world coffee organizations also predicted that east
Africa could become a significant market player on the
international coffee market within the foreseeable future, the
paper added.
</P>
<P>
The average yield in east Africa's coffee producing countries
is only some 250 kilograms per hectare while many Latin American
and some Asian countries harvest an average of more than one ton
per hectare.
</P>
<P>
The east African region produces close to 840,000 tons of
mostly arabica coffee, enough for the region to be a competitor
of Colombia, which is the world's second largest coffee producer.
</P>
</TEXT>
