<HEADLINE> 31 People Killed in Cattle Rustling in West Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan police has confirmed
that 31 people including nine raiders were killed on Saturday
when armed rustlers attacked Turkana District, west Kenya, the
Daily Nation reported today.
</P>
<P>
Police sources said the raiders believed to be from Uganda
attacked Lorengipi in Turkana District on Saturday morning,
killing five herdsmen and taking away hundreds of animals.
</P>
<P>
Seven of the raiders were also killed in the attack, two of
them wearing uniforms similar to those issued to Kenya Police
reservists.
</P>
<P>
During another attack, five women and eight children were
killed and more than 200 camels and 40 head of cattle were
stolen.
</P>
<P>
Police sources said that the animals were recovered after
heavy fighting between Kenyan security personnel and cattle
rustlers just as the latter were about to cross the border into
Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Reuben Rotich, Turkana District Commissioner was quoted as
confirming the attacks, adding that the security personnel were
still on the ground.
</P>
<P>
The daily newspaper said that security personnel travelling in
a lorry to the conflict area were ambushed Sunday at Loya, near
the border between Kenya and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Police re-enforcement had to be brought in from Baringo and
Nakuru to prevent the raiders from crossing into Uganda, the
paper pointed out.
</P>
<P>
More than 60 people have died in raids between security
personnel and cattle rustlers in Turkana and Pokot district over
the past three months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
