<DOCNO> XIE19970922.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Theory of China Threat to Food Security Refuted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The prediction that China
will pose a threat to the world food security is "totally
groundless," a Chinese official said here today.
</P>
<P>
"With a small amount of grain imported, China will by no means
be a threat to the world food security," Sun Xiaoyu,
vice-president of the Development Research Center of the State
Council of China, told a World Bank seminar.
</P>
<P>
"In a historical perspective, China did not rely much on the
international grain market," Sun said at the seminar entitled
"China: Food Security and the Rural Economy."
</P>
<P>
For example, China had been a net exporter of food between 1985
and 1995 when its total exports of food reached 75.6 billion US
dollars while imports stood at 34 billion US dollars, he said.
</P>
<P>
The theory of grain threat from China is "totally groundless,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Lester Brown, in his book "Who Will Feed China?" published in
1996, alleged that with rapid economic and population growth,
China may have to import all the grain in the international market
by the year 2020, and as a result, may starve people in Africa
and other regions.
</P>
<P>
Sun said that in the 21st century, China will continue to rely
on its own resources to be largely self-sufficient in grain
supply. In a normal situation, the self-sufficiency rate of grain
is no lower than 95 percent, and the net import does not exceed
five percent of domestic consumption, he added.
</P>
<P>
China uses only seven percent of the world's arable land to
feed 22 percent of the world's population. Its total grain output
reached 490 million tons in 1996, up five percent from the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
At today's seminar, Justin Yifu Lin, director of the China
Center for Economic Research at Beijing University, agreed with
Sun's view, saying that Lester Brown's prediction was not
accurate.
</P>
<P>
"Land is not the most important issue, the more important issue
is how much you can produce from per unit of land," said the
Chinese scholar. He forecasts that China's grain output would be
doubled in the coming 20 to 30 years, if the government could
invest sufficiently in agricultural research and irrigation
systems.
</P>
<P>
He further noted that "if China can increase its grain import,
that will be a main contribution to the peaceful environment in
the world since many disputes between North America, Europe and
Australia arise from grain surplus."
</P>
<P>
The World Bank published a report here today, predicting that
China can continue to feed its population over the next two or
three decades and domestic food production can largely keep pace
with population growth.
</P>
<P>
China can overcome obstacles to growth in agriculture by
improving agricultural research, upgrading irrigation systems, and
developing more arable land, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
