<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Minister said United Front Government Safe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 22 (Xinhua)-- Indian Union Home Minister
Indrajit Gupta today said that there is not immediate threat to
the United Front (UF) government as the Congress party, outside
supporter to the government, could not afford to withdraw support
at this juncture.
</P>
<P>
Talking to newsmen here on his way back from his two-day visit
to the country's border districts, Gupta said that the Congress
was in no hurry to withdraw support to the UF government.
</P>
<P>
The UF government is a minority government at the Center and it
will not last for a single day without the support of the Congress
party. In the last general election held in April-May last year,
both the national parties of the Congress and the Bharatiya Janata
Party (BJP) failed to win a simple majority in Parliament. In
order to prevent the BJP, referred to as communal party by most of
other political parties, from coming into power at the Center, the
Congress supported multi-regional parties, which later formed the
UF, to form a Union government last year.
</P>
<P>
The Congress withdrew its support to the UF government headed
by Deve Gowda at the end of March this year accusing Gowda of
trying to weaken the Congress. The Deve Gowda government fell
since then and Inder Kumar Gujral replaced him as the UF
government new prime minister.
</P>
<P>
In the past few weeks, Congress President Sitaram Kesri has
time and again said that the present UF government could not last
long as the regional parties had inherent differences. The
Congress party would not allow the government to pass another
budget in February next year. He has asked his party men to
prepare for mid-term elections. He even said that facts have shown
that the coaliton government at the Center was a failure.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether the UF would remain united in the event of a
mid-term poll, Gupta said it was too early to anticipate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
