<DOCNO> XIE19970922.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Seeks International Cooperation to Control Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Beijing is to host the
International Cooperation Conference on Environmental Protection
Projects from November 20 to 21.
</P>
<P>
China has prepared nearly 70 priority projects on pollution
control for the conference, which is the country's first meeting
of the kind seeking international cooperation in environmental
protection, officials said.
</P>
<P>
They added that it will help overseas funds and enterprises
enter China's environmental protection market, and push forward
the implementation of the country's environmental protection plans.
</P>
<P>
The projects cover water and air pollution control, disposal of
urban waste and hazardous waste and protection of ecology and
biodiversity.
</P>
<P>
Carefully selected from the nearly 2,000 key projects in the
China Trans-Century Green Project Plan, the 70 programs are not
only urgently needed, but also well-prepared, officials said,
adding that the projects have gained support from the State and
local planning commissions.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Kunmin, deputy-director of the National Environmental
Protection Agency, said in today's news conference that to seek
extensive and concrete international cooperation has always been
an important way for China to attain its environmental protection
goals.
</P>
<P>
He hopes that the international community, such as the World
Bank, the Asian Development Bank, the United Nations Development
Program, the United Nations Environment Program, foreign
governments, trans-national financial institutions and enterprises
could take active part in China's environmental protection work.
</P>
<P>
China still faces a serious environmental situation. Pollution
in the urban areas is extending to the countryside, and in some
regions, pollution has become a leading obstacle to local economic
and social development.
</P>
<P>
To control pollution and improve the environment, China has
announced the Trans-century Green Project Plan. In the first phase
(1996-2000) of the plan, the country plans to spend some 22.5
billion US dollars on pollution control.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
