<HEADLINE> Australia Pledges More Assistance to PNG </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister John Howard
today pledged further Australian assistance to the drought-ravaged
South Pacific country of Papua New Guinea (PNG) on top of the
360,000 U.S. dollars already committed by his government.
</P>
<P>
Haward told the parliament that he had made the pledge during a
meeting with PNG Prime Minister Bill Skate at last week's South
Pacific Forum in the Cook Islands.
</P>
<P>
The PNG prime minister estimated that 700,000 of his country's
4.3 million people are suffering as a result of the drought that
is caused by the El Nino weather pattern, according to earlier
reports.
</P>
<P>
"I had a discussion with the prime minister of PNG about this
issue late last week and I indicated that after further assessment
had been made it would be the intention of the Australian
government to give further assistance," Howard said.
</P>
<P>
"I think we do have a special obligation to our neighbor in
this time of particular need," he added.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Alexander Downer also told the parliament
today that Australia had responded immediately to a request from
the PNG government on September 10 for drought assistance.
</P>
<P>
Reports said a Royal Australian Air Force (RAAF) Hercules today
landed in the PNG capital of Port Moresby to begin a four-day
operation to provide relief supplies for remote villages.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the RAAF flight, Australian experts have also
been sent to that country to assess the extent of damage caused by
drought.  
</P>
</TEXT>
