<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 12:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak Embarks on Moscow Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak today embarked on a three-day visit to Moscow that is
aimed to reinvigorate economic ties, the Egyptian Middle East News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The visit, at the invitation of Russian President Boris
Yeltsin, is the first by an Arab leader in six years to Moscow
after the former Soviet Union collapsed in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Kamal el-Ganzouri and Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa as well as 24 businessmen are accompanying the president on
the tour.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak has urged Russia to promote its role in salvaging the
stalled Mideast peace process. Russia, together with the U.S., is
the co-sponsor of the process that started after the 1991 Madrid
peace conference.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak and Yeltsin will sign a package of pacts on eliminating
double taxation, protecting investment and scientific, security and
judicial cooperation.
</P>
<P>
They are also expected to deal with the issue of enlarging the
U.N. Security Council. Egypt is angling for a permanent membership
on the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The presidents will co-chair the Higher Egyptian-Russian
Committee to probe bilateral issues in the political and economic
domains, as well as the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Trade and Supply Minister Ahmed Goweili is already in Moscow
for meetings of the joint committee which will thrash out a number
of proposals to give a push to the bilateral trade.
</P>
<P>
The proposals comprise the establishment of a joint trade, an
marketing company, a joint Egyptian-Russian bank to fund trade
transactions between the two sides and a large exhibition in
Moscow showcasing Egyptian exports in October.
</P>
<P>
At the close of their ministerial committee meetings Sunday,
Egypt and Russia have approved the establishment of three joint
companies to work in the fields of agricultural, industrial
exports and marine transport.
</P>
<P>
Trade volume between the two countries during the first six
months of the year reached 172.4 million dollars, 18.8 million of
which are Egyptian exports. Cairo and Moscow expect to expand
their trade to one billion dollars from the current 380-400
million dollars a year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
