<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhu Rongji Pledges Eventual Full RMB Yuan Convertibility </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Zhu
Rongji today pledged that China will certainly make the Renminbi
yuan fully convertible in the future, but said it needs time to
achieve such a goal.
</P>
<P>
Zhu told participants of a World Bank seminar on China's
economy here this afternoon that the Chinese authorities have been
advised by all international friends to be extremely careful in
considering to make the yuan convertible under the capital
account.
</P>
<P>
The yuan has become convertible under the current account since
last December but is still regulated under the capital account.
</P>
<P>
China will eventually make it fully convertible when the
nation's industrial structure is rationalized and supervision over
the banking sector by the central bank is improved, Zhu said when
answering questions from the audience after delivering a speech.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that China's foreign exchange reserves have hit
131.6 billion U.S. dollars to date, and is expected to surpass 140
billion U.S. dollars by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of China's banking sector, Zhu reiterated China's
commitment to further opening the sector to foreign businesses,
noting that more than 500 foreign banks have set up representative
offices in China.
</P>
<P>
A number of foreign banks have established branches in the
country and nine of them have been approved to conduct RMB yuan
business in Shanghai, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also welcomed foreign insurance companies to develop
business in China, saying that the Chinese authorities are
considering to approve British and Australian insurance companies
to enter the Chinese market, after a few companies from the U.S.,
Canada, Switzerland and Germany have already won the approval.
</P>
<P>
"You are welcome to China. That will be conducive to China's
economic development, but you should take into account the market
capacity," Zhu said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
