<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Calls on U.N. to Back Sanctions on Sierra </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS) has called on the international community
to back its sanctions against Sierra Leone to force out the
military government of that country.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS's appeal was voiced by Nigerian Foreign Minister Tom
Ikimi at the weekend at the U.N. Security Council on behalf of
the ECOWAS Committee of Five on Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS approved sanctions and blockade on Sierra Leone on
August 30, after negotiations failed to persuade Major Johnny
Kromah to return power to elected President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah,
whom he overthrew in a coup on May 25.
</P>
<P>
Ikimi condemned the Kromah government of having "shown little
sign of flexibility, accommodation or a disposition to
compromise" and held it responsible for the breakdown of the
Abidjan talks.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the fear that the inflow of arms and ammunition
to Sierra Leone is a sign that Kromah is fortifying himself for a
prolonged engagement.
</P>
<P>
Ikimi also expressed regret over the worsening situation in
Sierra Leone, where the number of refugees are multiplying,
social infrastructures are being stretched to their limits,
foreign nations are constantly harassed and ECOWAS personnel are
frequently attacked.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he urged the Security Council to take decisive
actions on the Sierra Leone crisis by applying the regime of
sanctions and embargo imposed by ECOWAS.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan has reportedly pledged his
support for the efforts of ECOWAS in a meeting with the ECOWAS
team, according to media reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
