<HEADLINE> Australia's AIDS Threat From New Guinea: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The most direct threat of
HIV/AIDS spreading from the neighboring region to Australia was
from the southern coast of the island of New Guinea, Australian
Health Minister Michael Wooldridge said today.
</P>
<P>
The coastal Irian Jaya village of Merauke had an infection rate
second only to the Indonesian capital Jakarta and the spread had
been "very rapid" in Papua New Guinea's Daru/Fly River region, the
minister told reporters at the World Health Organization (WHO)
Western Pacific Region's annual conference in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
There were 30,000 visits a year from that region to Australia
under international treaty obligations, presenting a threat to the
Aboriginal population in particular, the Australian Associated
Press said.
</P>
<P>
"That is where a potential threat lies and the Aboriginal
Health Strategy ... is focusing very much on sexual health,
largely targeting northern Australia, and trying to prevent what
could be a problem in the future," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The number of Australians with AIDS or HIV virus is relatively
low and stable compared with other countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
He pointed to some good results in the AIDS war in the region,
particularly in Thailand and Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
"As to the threat to Australia, yes there is a threat from
travel, and we have been working very hard in our AusAID projects
with sex workers in parts of the region, " he said. AusAID is
Australia's official overseas assistance agency.
</P>
<P>
WHO Western Region Director Sang Tae Han said the "powderkeg"
for AIDS in South-East Asia would be Cambodia, Vietnam and part of
Laos, as well as Thailand, Burma and India further west.
</P>
<P>
"In the (Pacific) region I don't think it will be as serious as
in our neighboring region," the director said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970922.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Ringggit Hits 27 Year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 22 (Xinhua)-- Malaysia's currency --
Ringgit today ended lower against the U.S. dollar, hitting a
27-year low.
</P>
<P>
The unit ended at 3.0950/10 to the dollar against 3.0280/20 at
last week's close. The rate was the lowest since 1970 when the
local unit was traded at a low of 3.0775.
</P>
<P>
Dealers attributed the weaker ringgit to continued absence of
buying support against a backdrop of a stronger greenback.
</P>
<P>
The sentiment of the currency market was also affected by
lackadaisical performance on the stock market whose 100-stock
Composite Index closed today at 760.50 points, 27.34 points or
3.47 percent lower than last week's closing.
</P>
<P>
The local currency also ended easier against other currencies,
at 2.0271/17 to the Singapore dollar from 1.9943/83, at 2.5199/50
against the yen from 2.4881/24, at 1.7316/48 against the mark from
1.6997 and at 4.9659/55 to the Pound from 4.8766/28 on the last
trading day.  
</P>
</TEXT>
