<DOCNO> XIE19970922.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senior Banking Official on China's Two Financial Systems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The monetary relationship
between the Chinese mainland and Hong Kong can be best summarized
as one country with two currencies, two monetary systems and two
mutually independent monetary authorities, Chen Yuan, deputy
governor of the People's Bank of China, said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a World Bank seminar on the 21st Century Economic
Outlook, Chen said Hong Kong will continue to maintain its own
system of currency issuance and management and that the HK dollar
will continue to circulate as the legal tender in Hong Kong, as
the Renminbi in the mainland.
</P>
<P>
The HK dollar will be treated as a foreign currency in the
mainland, he said. Likewise, he added, the Renminbi will be
treated as a foreign currency in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The three note-issuing banks in Hong Kong will continue to
issue Hong Kong dollar bank notes, with 100 percent backing by
U.S. dollars under the linked exchange rate system, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The co-existence of the two currencies in China reflects the
existing differences in the economic systems in Hong Kong and the
mainland and is called for by the ongoing economic reform and
opening-up in the mainland," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The Hong Kong Monetary Authority (HKMA) shall independently
conduct the monetary policy in Hong Kong and be accountable solely
to the Hong Kong government. The People's Bank of China will not
take the place of the HKMA," Chen said.
</P>
<P>
He said the HKMA will continue to supervise financial
institutions in Hong Kong, including those from the mainland, and
such supervision will continue to be performed in accordance with
international rules and practices.
</P>
<P>
The financial institutions established in the mainland by Hong
Kong investors will continue to be treated as foreign financial
institutions and enjoy the same preferential treatment as other
foreign financial institutions, he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is very important for Hong Kong as an international
financial center to continue to develop its international monetary
relations and participate in the activities of international and
regional financial institutions as well as central bank forums,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Basic Law stipulates that the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region may, using the name of "Hong Kong, China",
maintain and develop financial relations and handle external
financial issues with other countries and regions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
