<HEADLINE> U.S.-Israel-Turkey Joint Maneuvers Condemned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami today condemned the forthcoming joint military maneuvers
by Turkey, Israel and the United States in the Mediterranean,
calling the move a threat to the whole region.
</P>
<P>
Addressing large crowds of people in the capital's Azadi
(Freedom) Square on the occasion of the Defense Week, Khatami said
the joint maneuvers were aimed to create tension in the area.
</P>
<P>
The joint military maneuvers involving troops of the three
countries will take place in mid-November in eastern Mediterranean
for the purpose of what Ankara said research and rescue training.
</P>
<P>
"Under pressures from the U.S., the Turkish government totally
ignored the concerns and anger of the Arab and Muslim states and
has submitted to this humiliation," he said.
</P>
<P>
This is indicative of the enemies' resolve to create tensions
in the region and to impose threat to regional stability as well
as Iran's security, he added.
</P>
<P>
"The Islamic Iran abstains from conflicts but will not
tolerate interference in its internal affairs (by foreign
countries)," said Khatami, "the country is fully prepared to
defend its territorial integrity and independence."
</P>
<P>
"The independence- and freedom-seeking nations, including Iran,
are continuously threatened by the hegemonic and expansionist
powers of the world, which mandates us to strengthen our armed
forces," he said.
</P>
<P>
Highlighting the role of country's armed forces in confronting
the threats, Khatami said Iran owes its independence to the
sacrifices of the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Eight years of "sacred defense" in the war with Iraq has
solidified the country's independence and it is incumbent upon the
nation to keep the memories of these struggles alive, said the
president.
</P>
<P>
Khatami called on the armed forces to continuously endeavor to
fulfill the nation's goal of preserving its independence.
</P>
<P>
Iran's armed forces staged a grand parade in the square in
commemorating the beginning of the 1980-88 war between Iran and
Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
