<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Set New Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
jumped 1.3 percent to a record high today as money continued to be
shifted away from resources and into industrial stocks,
particularly the banks.
</P>
<P>
The trend saw Australia's most profitable bank National
Australia Bank (NAB) overtake Australia's resources giant BHP Co.
to become the largest stock on the Australian Stock Exchange by
market capitalization.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index rose 34.5 points to close just shy of
its intraday high at 2764.9, eclipsing its previous record close
of 2745.9 set on July 2.
</P>
<P>
The interest rate-sensitive banking and investment and finance
sectors were the highlights, along with the tourism and leisure
and alcohol and tobacco indices.
</P>
<P>
Mercantile Mutual's Greg Matthews said the recent trend of
investors exiting resource stocks amid pessimism relating to the
commodity outlook continued today.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index ended 63.1 points, or 1.4 percent,
higher at 4579.0, while the all resources index added just 11.3
points, or 0.85 percent, to 1333.7.
</P>
<P>
The banking index put on 2.11 percent, with NAB 35 cents
stronger at 22.25 Australian dollars, Westpac up 27 cents, or 3.13
percent, to 8.90 Australian dollars on turnover of 10 million
shares, ANZ bank 26 cents firmer at 11.38 Australian dollars and
CBA bank up 33.8 cents at 17.28 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Sugar and building materials concern CSR jumped 20 cents to
5.90 Australian dollars and Coca-Cola Amatil rose 27 cents to
15.05 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the resources side, BHP staged a slight recovery to finish
eight cents up at 15.78 Australian dollars after bottoming at
15.53 Australian dollars earlier in the session. Turnover was 14.5
million shares.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere, mining giant Rio Tinto added 30 cents to 21.12
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index closed 1.9 points up at 1250.4, with spot gold
at 320.70 U.S. dollars an ounce compared to 320.85 U.S. dollars at
Friday's close in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
National turnover totaled 324.58 million shares valued at 1.3
billion Australian dollars (93.6 million U.S. dollars) with
rising issues beating falls by 690 to 538. 
</P>
</TEXT>
