<HEADLINE> Transnational Accounting Firm Moves Forward With Business in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The World-renowned accounting
firm, Arthur Andersen, has been gearing up to make the most of
business opportunities in China, including Hong Kong and Taiwan,
which have appeared as a result of Hong Kong's return to the
motherland.
</P>
<P>
The company recently appointed Albert Ng, a senior partner in
the firm, as managing partner of its China business and the
executive responsible for implementing the strategy.
</P>
<P>
The firm hopes to expand its business by treating interior
areas, the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region and Taiwan as a
single market by making rational use of technological forces and
labor resources, and further improving coordination of businesses
in these areas, according to a report from the company.
</P>
<P>
In a move to secure its position as a leading professional
service agency in the Asia-Pacific region, the accounting firm
expects to double the size of its practice in China by the turn of
the century.
</P>
<P>
"With Arthur Andersen's success and growth in China, and our
vision of the China strategy, I have decided to pass on my
responsibilities as managing partner in China. Our China practice
has grown to a point where it demands the full attention and focus
of a dedicated leader," said John Burrows, Arthur Andersen
Asia-Pacific regional managing partner.
</P>
<P>
Ng joined Arthur Andersen's Hong Kong office in 1981. He was
transferred to the Sydney office in 1989 where he remained for two
years as a manager. In 1994, he moved to Shanghai as managing
partner, a position he will continue to hold in addition to his
China-wide responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
Ng said: "China will become a place with the fastest growth in
our global business expansion, and as events unfold, China,
including Hong Kong and Taiwan, will become a more integrated
market unit."
</P>
<P>
Arthur Andersen has pioneered professional services in China
since 1979, and established the first Sino-foreign certified
public accounting firm, Arthur Andersen-Huaqiang, in 1982.
</P>
<P>
Arthur Andersen currently has offices in Beijing, Shanghai,
Shenzhen and the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR), with
a total of 1,100 employees.
</P>
<P>
The company has led the profession in helping China approach
the international capital markets by assisting 39 enterprises from
interior areas of China to list their securities on domestic and
overseas bourses, with a total value of about five billion
U.S. dollars, and has also served over 50 power plants in ten
provinces in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
