<HEADLINE> Opinion Poll Shows Corruption Is Rampant In Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Ninety-five percent of
Bangladeshi people consider the police department as the most
corrupt organization, according to a country-wide opinion poll
conducted recently by Bangladesh Unnayan Parishad (BUP).
</P>
<P>
The results of the poll were published today by local newspaper
the Daily Star.
</P>
<P>
The BUP poll said that the customs department comes next with
91 percent, and tax department, secretariat and judiciary rank
third, fourth and fifth respectively.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-two percent of the respondents believed that government
officials are mainly responsible for all such corruption, the poll
continued.
</P>
<P>
According to another recently-made study on the corruption, the
Bangladesh's economy crippled with corruption i.e., the
'underground economy' in the country consists of 23 percent of
formal GDP.
</P>
<P>
The unrecorded part of export and import sectors consists of
1.7 percent and 9.1 percent of GDP, and 12 percent and 39.4
percent of formal export and import sectors respectively, the
study stated.
</P>
<P>
The study added that as an import-dependent country of
Bangladesh, import sector is a major source of earning illegal
money through corruption.
</P>
<P>
According to some estimate, the cost of corruption comes to
almost 350 percent of initial official costs of setting up a
garments factory, and when yearly renewal costs are added, this
figure increases to nearly 700 percent.
</P>
<P>
The major portion of this cost of corruption is bribe, the
study said, adding that bribe constitutes 60 percent of the
initial cost and about 95 percent of yearly renewal costs.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Star quoted Humayun Kabir, Assistant Professor of
Department of Economics of Shahjalal University as saying that
corruption has pervaded all the sectors of Bangladesh's economy
and it has rather emerged as a status symbol.
</P>
<P>
Kabir pointed out that the presence of corruption is costly for
the common life of the people and sufferings are unbearable at
individual level.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970922.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Capital Flows to Emerging Markets Hit New High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hong Kong, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Private capital flows to
emerging markets hit a new peak of 235.2 billion U.S. dollars in
1996 from 192.8 billion dollars the previous year, according to a
report released by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) here
today.
</P>
<P>
The factors which helped propel private capital flows to the
emerging markets include the low level of interest rates in Japan
and Germany and the compression of corporate bond spreads in the
United States, the report said.
</P>
<P>
That prompted fixed-income investors in the mature markets to
move down the credit spectrum and search for higher yields on
emerging market debt, said the report, entitled "International
Capital Markets."
</P>
<P>
It also attributed the surge in private capital flows to the
improved economic performance in many emerging market economies
which reduced perceived credit risks.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held here today, David Folkerts-Landau,
assistance director of the Research Department of the IMF, said
the emerging market countries should make significant improvements
in market infrastructure including higher transparency in policies
and regulations to attract more private capitals.
</P>
<P>
The pattern of capital flows to emerging markets suggests that
private financing is still provided on a selective basis, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
These flows have been highly concentrated, with top 10 emerging
markets receiving nearly three-quarters of capital inflows during
the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Asia remained the largest recipient of capital flows totaling
1.068 trillion U.S. dollars in 1996 although the growth of total
flows moderated sharply from 32 percent in 1995 to eight percent
last year.
</P>
<P>
The relatively modest expansions of capital flows to Asia
reflected the slowdown in the growth of both export and output in
the region, as well as the impact of uncertainties created by
financial sector weaknesses in countries such as the Republid of
Korea and Thailand, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Total private capital flows to Latin America rebounded
robustly, more than doubling from their depressed levels in 1995
of 35.7 billion U.S. dollars to 77.7 billion U.S. dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The sharp rebound raised total flows to the region above the
previous peak in 1993, completing the recovery of total flows from
the effects of the Mexican crisis.
</P>
<P>
While capital flows to the Middle East and Europe grew
strongly, flows to Africa and the transition economies declined,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
Since 1995, net foreign direct investment (FDI) has accounted
for the largest proportion of the private capital flows to
emerging markets, and in 1996, it stood at 1.059 trillion U.S.
dollars, accounting for some 45 percent of the total flows.
</P>
<P>
FDI flows to emerging market countries expanded between
1991-1995 at an average annual rate of 37 percent, and continued
to grow robustly during 1996, increasing by 21 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970922.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Broken Coupler Blamed for Philippine Train Collision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- A broken coupler is blamed for
the collision of two commuter trains during rush hours early this
morning in the southern suburb of Manila, Philippine National
Railways (PNR) spokesman Reynaldo Recede said this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The PNR reported only seven deaths so far, and hundreds
injured, scattered for treatment in various hospitals near the
site of the collision. But earlier report said 10 people were
killed.
</P>
<P>
However, Recede said, the PNR has not yet determined why the
coupler separated from the engine of commuter train 302.
</P>
<P>
Train 302 had just left Sucat station for the next stop at
Bicutan when its three coaches suddenly jerked and started moving
backward, Recede said.
</P>
<P>
The fourth coach, which housed the engine, was left intact in
the middle of the railway tracks, and its driver and conductor
unharmed.
</P>
<P>
At this juncture, train 304, which had left Calamba for Manila,
was coming in to Bicutan station. There was no way out for its
driver, and it crashed headlong onto the earlier train.
</P>
<P>
Both trains have a normal capacity of 106 passengers per coach,
but during rush hours, passengers defy PNR rules and occupy even
the roofs and spaces between coaches.
</P>
<P>
Recede said the PNR has dispatched emergency medical teams to
the scene of the accident, and coordinating the disposition of
bodies strewn all over the place.
</P>
<P>
He also revealed that the commuter trains were fitted in the
early 70's and maintained properly through the years.  
</P>
