<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Speed up Infrastructural Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 22 (Xinhua) -- China will accelerate its
infrastructural construction in the next 20-odd years through a
series of new measures, Yao Zhenyan, governor of the State
Development Bank of China, said here today.
</P>
<P>
At a World Bank seminar entitled "21st Century's Economy of
China," Yao said the Chinese government has set special
construction funds for power industry, railways, post and
telecommunication services, highways and ports to support the
development of the key infrastructural projects.
</P>
<P>
The central and local governments will jointly fund the key
projects, and the central government will adopt favorable policies
toward the infrastructural projects in the central and western
regions, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government also encourages foreign investment to
join in China's infrastructural construction, he said, adding that
foreign funds are expected to be put into hydropower projects,
construction of local railways, urban subways and highways, and
civil airports.
</P>
<P>
He said China has set up the development bank to support the
key state infrastructural projects.
</P>
<P>
According to Yao, by the end of 1996, the bank has allocated
284.2 billion yuan (33.8 billion U.S. dollars) for the key
projects in communications and power industry.
</P>
<P>
From 1979 to 1996, China's power generating capacity increased
by 8.3 percent per year. By the end of 1996, the installing
capacity of the power industry reached 236 million kilowatts and
the generating capacity was 107.94 billion kilowatt hours, which
ranks second in the world.
</P>
<P>
On the communication and transportation industry, he said that
in the past five years, the length of China's railways has
extended 4,365 kilometers to more than 60,000 kilometers; the
newly built and re-constructed highways were 100,000 kilometers
with 19,000-kilometer high-grade ones. China now has 406 deep
water berths and 142 civil airports.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, China's infrastructural basis is still weak
compared with the developed countries and it expects to be further
enhanced in the next two decades.
</P>
<P>
Jack Cizain, vice-president of the International Division of
Electricite de France, said his company was very much impressed by
the rapid growth of China's power industry in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
China will create a new situation in its infrastructural
construction to face new finance challenges, he added.
</P>
<P>
He also said he was confident about China's power market and
expects further cooperation with China's power industry.
</P>
<P>
Joseph Ferrigno, president and chief executive officer of
Prudential Asia Infrastructure Investors Ltd., said China has lots
of successful projects in infrastructural construction.
</P>
<P>
He advised Chinese government officials in charge of business
affairs to know more about risks in allocation of financial
resources and to make more efforts in perfecting legal systems.
</P>
<P>
China has the capacity to make its market more attractive to
the world in the future, Ferrigno said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
