<HEADLINE> Promotion Event To Be Held To Attract More Hong Kong Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 22 (Xinhua) -- An investment promotion event
will be held in Hong Kong early next month for the purpose of
encouraging more investment into China's mainland, especially the
inland area, from this special administrative region.
</P>
<P>
According to the Chinese Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Co-operation (MOFTEC), the organizer of the event, the promotion
and a subsequent investment symposium are scheduled from October
7-11.
</P>
<P>
The annual activity, also the first large trade promotion event
organized by the ministry in Hong King since its return to the
motherland, boasts the largest number of participants as well as
projects since the event was kicked off in 1994, according to
Deputy Director of the Foreign Investment Administration of the
MOFTEC Hu Jingyan.
</P>
<P>
China's 29 provinces, cities and autonomous regions, including
14 from the inland area, will send a 250-member delegation with a
total of 889 projects to the event.
</P>
<P>
Heilongjiang Province in northeast China, with 91 projects,
ranks first in terms of quantity, and the Tibet Autonomous Region
will participate for the first time, bringing along 19 projects.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturing and construction projects are on the top of the
list, with totals of 553 and 127 respectively, accounting for 62.2
and 14.3 percent of the entire number.
</P>
<P>
At the symposium to be held following the event, officials from
MOFTEC, the State Planning Commission, and other government
departments will give a thorough explanation of China's foreign
investment policy, the long-term plan for national economic
development and its priority, China's financial market, tax system
for foreign companies, as well as new policies of customs
supervision and control.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that Hong Kong, as the mainland's largest
source of foreign investment, had funneled an accumulated 109.5
billion US dollars of funding into the mainland by the end of the
first half of 1997.
</P>
<P>
This event, according to Hu, is expected to further strengthen
the economic and trade ties between China's mainland and Hong
Kong, and enhance Hong Kong people's understanding about the
mainland's policy on drawing direct investment, especially to the
middle and western parts of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
