<HEADLINE> South Korean President's Son Demanded 7-year Imprisonment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 22 (Xinhua) -- South Korean prosecutors
demanded Monday a seven-year jail term as well as huge fines for
president Kim Young-sam's son, Kim Hyun-chul, on charges of
receiving bribes and tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Prosecutor's office demanded Junior Kim 1.5 billion
won (1.67 million U.S. dollars) in fines on alleged tax evasion
and ordered return of an additional 3,274.2 million won (3.82
million dollars) on alleged bribes.
</P>
<P>
Junior Kim, 38, was arrested May 17 on charges of
influence-peddling and tax evasion. It was found that he received
a total of 6.61 billion won (7.36 million dollars) from six
businessmen from 1993 until the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
In a trial session at the Seoul District Court, the prosecution
stated that the case involving Kim Hyun-chul was an illegal and
corrupt scandal committed by core people within the power group.
</P>
<P>
"Their acceptance of large amounts of money from businesses
over an extended period of time cannot be justified under any
circumstances," the prosecution said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, prison terms ranging from 1.5 to five years were
also sought by the prosecution for other five defendants in the
case, including former senior intelligence official Kim Ki-sup and
Junior Kim's close aide Par tae-jung.
</P>
<P>
The ruling trial for Junior Kim and the other defendants is
scheduled to be held on October 13, according to the court
sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
