<HEADLINE> Chinese President Meets Finnish President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
said here today that China is satisfied with the positive
development trend of the Sino-Finish relationship, and thanked the
Finnish government for its efforts to promote bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Jiang made the comment at a meeting with Finnish President
Martti Ahtisaari, who stopped in China on his way to Japan.
</P>
<P>
Extending a welcome to Ahtisaari, Jiang said it is his first
meeting with a foreign head of state since the 15th National
Congress of the Communist Party of China (CPC), at which he was
again elected General Secretary of the CPC Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
Jiang recalled that the meeting was his fourth with the Finnish
President since 1995, when the two men first met in Moscow to
attend celebrations marking the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
Last year, President Ahtisaari visited China and the two
leaders had productive talks. Jiang said that at the turn of the
century, leaders of the two countries should keep frequent
contacts and exchange of views on bilateral and international
issues, which would be conducive to deepening mutual understanding
and enhancing cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The Sino-Finnish ties have been normal and good, Jiang
said. Especially in recent years, the cooperation between the two
sides has continued to develop in political, economic and all
other fields. The bilateral exchanges in cultural, educational and
judicial areas have also been extensive.
</P>
<P>
He said China highly values its economic and trade relations
with Finland, adding that the economies of the two countries are
complementary and hold bright promise for future cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Jiang hoped that the two governments would encourage their
enterprises to strengthen direct contacts and cooperation. He
believed the Sino-Finnish economic ties and trade would develop
further with the joint efforts of the two sides.
</P>
<P>
President Ahtisaari congratulated Jiang on the success of the
15th National Congress of the CPC, and said Finland followed the
Congress with great interest as the event would have a great
impact on China's development. He said 1997 has been an important
year for China, and that the return of Hong Kong and the
successful convening of the Congress would effectively guarantee
China's development.
</P>
<P>
Finland has always highly valued its relations with China and
has been satisfied with the development of the bilateral economic
ties and trade, the President said. Finland wishes to work
together with China to further strengthen the bilateral friendly
cooperation, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents also exchanged views on other bilateral
issues and some international issues of common interest. 
</P>
