<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Haze Blankets Parts of Southern Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- A gray haze has blanketed part
of the Southern Philippines for over two weeks, although a weather
bureau official cannot confirm if this is part of the haze
affecting Malaysia, Indonesia, Brunei and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine News Agency reported today that the greater part
of the Southern Mindanao, including the southern city of
Zamboanga, have been blanketed by the haze.
</P>
<P>
The Bureau of Air Transportation has already banned the takeoff
or landing of aircraft in the Zamboanga International Airport
since four days ago due to a "moderate haze" now blankets the city
and the airport, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
With this ruling, only instrument-rated pilots and aircraft
equipped for instrument landing are allowed to land airport.
</P>
<P>
Sarrama Sahi, officer-in-charge of the Philippine Atmospheric,
Geophysical and Astronomical Services Administration, said that
the "haze" in Zamboanga is "unusual".
</P>
<P>
But her office cannot check the nature of the haze as there are
no facilities or equipment available to do that.
</P>
<P>
Mindanao and parts of the Visayas are within the same longitude
as these Asian countries which have been affected by the haze
caused by forest fires in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
In Zamboanga, residents have noted the haze as early as two
weeks ago, but took no special notice until the other Monday, when
the haze was not followed by heavy rains, as clouds usually do.
</P>
<P>
Sahi said this is the "first time" she noted this kind of haze
which reduced visibility to as short as a minimum of 5,000 meters
from her office located at the Zamboanga International Airport.
</P>
<P>
While the country's general outlook is that of cloudy because
of an "intertropical convergence zone," she said she cannot
explain why the nearby mountains, usually visible on sunny days,
have been covered by haze since over a week ago.
</P>
<P>
In the morning, the sun is just an orange ball and the average
visibility during the day is that experienced during an eclipse of
the sun.
</P>
<P>
In Basilan Province, the southern Mindanao, residents have
noted the haze for over a week because the Malanawi Island,
located across the local wharf, appears only as a hazy outline, as
if rains are falling across the waterline, although there are no
rains at all.
</P>
<P>
Resident in other part of southern Mindanao also reported that
big mountains about 10 kilometers away have disappeared in the
haze.  
</P>
</TEXT>
