<HEADLINE> Iranian Air Force Planes Join Massive War Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 22 (Xinhua) -- More than 150 jet fighters
and cargo planes took part in the ongoing massive war games near
the religious city of Qom, about 150 kilometers south of Tehran.
</P>
<P>
According to the official news agency IRNA today, Brigadier
General Habib Baqa'i, commander of the Air Force said those planes
were engaged in support activities to infantry and armored units.
</P>
<P>
About 200,000 soldiers of the air, ground and naval forces of
the Iranian Army participated in the most extensive military
exercises starting last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The three-phased maneuvers, code-named Zulfaqar and expected to
last until the end of the "Defense Week" on September 29, were
aimed at upgrading military power of the participating forces,
Baqa'i said.
</P>
<P>
"All kinds of the offensive and defensive equipment
manufactured by the Air Force are being deployed in the
exercises," he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Taking off from eight bases, the Air Force units pounded
positions of the hypothetical enemy to defend the maritime borders
of the country and render support to the infantry and armored
units.
</P>
<P>
Brigadier General Reza Nazem, communications commander of the
Ground Force, said modern communication facilities and locally
produced equipment are deployed and tested in the maneuvers.
</P>
</TEXT>
