<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tea Leaf Pilfering Gets Serious in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Safeguarding tea bushes in
the night has become a very difficult task to small tea farmers in
Sri Lanka these days as pilfering of green leaves is on the rise.
</P>
<P>
The local press reported today that stealing green leaves has
become very common in the tea growing areas of Matugama,
Agalawatta and Bulathsinhala, in Western Province.
</P>
<P>
Many pilferers started stealing, even robbing of other people's
tea leaves in the darkness of nights to earn a fast buck.
</P>
<P>
Green leaves are sold at an all time high price of 20 to 24
Rupees (0.34 to 0.41 U.S. dollars) a kilogram in these regions.
</P>
<P>
The majority of the small tea farmers in the area have
complained that safeguarding their plants from thieves has become
a difficult task for them, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Night watchers have been employed in some large tea
plantations.
</P>
<P>
But those small tea growers cannot afford to hire night
watchers. Most farmers keep the midnight oil burning to guard
their holdings.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970922.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vice-Premier Zhu on China's Opening-up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Zhu
Rongji reiterated China's basic policy of opening up to the
outside world here today at a seminar sponsored by the World Bank
on China's economic development prospects in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Delivering a keynote speech at the seminar, Zhu said that China
will continue to follow unswervingly the opening-up policy and
march to the world even more confidently.
</P>
<P>
He told the bankers and entrepreneurs present at the seminar
that China will reintroduce certain policy incentives towards the
import of equipment needed for the foreign-invested projects.
</P>
<P>
But these projects must conform to the industrial policies of
China and bring about new technologies, instead of repetitive
construction at low technological level, Zhu added.
</P>
<P>
He said that China has recently announced a sharp reduction of
the import and export tariffs effective from October 1, 1997,
involving more than 4,800 duty paragraphs of commodities, or more
than 73 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
After the reduction, the average tariffs will drop from 23
percent to 17 percent, down 26 percent. China has also undertaken
to reduce the customs level to the average level of developing
countries by the end of this century.
</P>
<P>
The vice-premier said that China will steadily open up the
market in light of the needs of reform and development.
</P>
<P>
"We will expedite the opening up of such infrastructure
industries as energy and communications and open up the service
sectors such as banking and domestic and foreign trade in a
step-by-step fashion," Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
He promised that China will protect the rights and interests of
foreign-funded enterprises according to law and grant them
national treatment so that all enterprises, Chinese or
foreign-funded, may compete on an equal footing.
</P>
<P>
Zhu also promised to improve the foreign-related legislation to
increase the transparency of trade regime, protect intellectual
property rights and improve trade and investment environment.
</P>
<P>
The vice-premier said that in the last five years of this
century China will add 80,000 MW to the installed capacity of
power generation, build 16,000 km railway lines and 2,800 km
expressway, lay a total length of 150,000 km of fiber optic lines
and install 80 million telephone switchboards. China's export and
import are expected to reach 400 billion U.S. dollars by the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
He welcomed all the friends from the industry and business
community present at the seminar to make investment in China and
to compete in the Chinese market.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said that China has actively participated in regional
economic cooperation and global multilateral trade system and has
made enormous efforts for its accession to the World Trade
Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
But it is unreasonable to make excessive demands on China,
which is a developing country, Zhu added.
</P>
<P>
"China's entry into WTO will benefit not only China's economic
development, but also world economic growth," Zhu said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970922.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Development Committee of W.Bank/IMF Pledges to Fight Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The Development Committee
of the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund (IMF) agreed
to make further efforts to fight the global problem of
corruption, the committee's Chairman Driss Jettou said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference following the 56th meeting of the
committee here, Jettou said participants at the meeting had
agreed that corruption and weak governance undermine
macro-economic stability, private sector activity and sustainable
development objectives, and may erode international support for
development cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The participants emphasized that corruption is a global problem
that requires complementary actions by all countries, according
to Jettou, who is also Moroccan Finance Minister.
</P>
<P>
While stressing that member governments have the primary
responsibility for combating corruption and strengthening
governance, the participants welcomed the more active involvement
of the Bank and the IMF, each within their respective mandate, in
responding to member governments' requests to strengthen their
institutions and performance in these areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
