<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poaching Appears in W. Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Poaching appeared in western
Uganda in recent years where a chimpanzee penis sold at 10,000
Ugandan Shillings (some ten U.S. Dollars), a report reaching here
said.
</P>
<P>
Uganda Wildlife Authority (UWA) officials said police detained
some suspected poachers in Fort Portal of western Uganda last
week.
</P>
<P>
Kibale National Park in the west of the country reported to
UWA that at least five chimpanzees have been killed since August
1994, four of them this year. The chimpanzees have been killed
both in conflicts with villagers and by poachers around the park.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of poaching, there appeared trafficking of
chimpanzee parts in the bordering areas between Uganda and the
Democratic Republic of Congo, the report said.
</P>
<P>
A skeleton of a chimpanzee sold at 50,000 to 60,000 Uganda
Shillings (some 60 U.S. dollars), the report added.
</P>
<P>
Researchers noted that expanding cultivation reduced the
surviving space for chimpanzees which invaded into plantations of
local peasants for food, causing conflicts between local people
and the beasts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
