<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading French newspapers today.
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- One year and a half after Italian Prime Minister Romano
Prodi came to power and several months ahead of the formal launch
of the European single currency, Italy has seemingly achieved
nothing on the way toward the euro. This is what Prodi will tell
President Jacques Chirac and Prime Minister Lionel Jospin when he
makes a brief visit to Paris today.
</P>
<P>
-- The campaign by the Social Democratic Party (SPD) of Germany
against "foreign criminals" and the euro in Hamburg turned out to
be a fiasco, as the party suffered a setback in the local
parliament election on Sunday, with its votes dropping from 40
percent in 1993 to 36 percent this time. Although the SPD claimed
that "Sunday would be the beginning of the end of the Kohl era,"
the Christian Democratic Union of Helmut Kohl won about 31 percent
of the votes. Henning Voscherau, the SPD mayor of Hamburg,
immediately announced his resignation.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- Minister of Environment Dominique Voynet has criticized
France's agricultural industry for causing pollution of water
resources. At a congress of a French environmentalist association
Sunday, Voynet said that it is necessary to cut subsidies for
cattle farms, criticizing farm chemical factories for polluting
the environment.
</P>
<P>
-- Polish television announced Sunday evening that the
opposition right-wing Solidarity Electoral Action has won most of
the votes in the legislative elections, with Social Democrats of
President Alekander Kwasniewski gaining 32.4 percent. The
Solidarity will form a coalition with Kwasniewski, who beat Lech
Walesa in the 1995 presidential election and is presiding the
country till 2000. 
</P>
