<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0700 GMT September 22 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING -- Chinese scientists will introduce cloning technology
to good fine strains of rare and valuable flowers.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the Chinese Academy of Foresty Sciences revealed
that the academy recently established a research center in Suzhou,
in east China's Jiangsu Province, to carry out related research.
</P>
<P>
Chinese roses, azaleas, and cold-resistant plants have been
included on the list for prospective cloning, with the
aforementioned sources pointing out that the academy will buy
patents and obtain needed facilities from abroad to promote
related experiments. (China-Clone-Flowers)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HONG KONG -- China's economy has become increasingly open and
it is still expanding its opening-up program faster and more
extensively, Chinese Vice-Premier Zhu Rongji said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
"In today's China, the policy of reform and opening-up has been
deeply rooted in the hearts of the people and is irreversible,"
Zhu said in English at the 56th Meeting of the Development
Committee of the World Bank/International Monetary Fund in Hong
Kong. (HK-Zhu Rongji-Economy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
COLOMBO -- A wealthy Tamil businessman has been arrested in
connection with an abortive rebel attempt to blow up the Ratmalana
Airport in the suburb of Colombo.
</P>
<P>
The businessman is alleged to have financed the Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) operations in Colombo, police sources
disclosed here Monday.
</P>
<P>
He had disappeared after police arrested two rebel activists
who were on a spying mission near the Ratmalana Airport. The
airport is being used as an airforce base. (Sri Lanka-Tamil
Businessman-Arrest)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- At least 10 people were killed and some 100 others
injured in a collision of commuter trains Monday morning in the
Southern Manila suburb, police said. (Philippines-Train Collision)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Thai Finance Minister Thanong Bidaya has stressed
that any political change in Thailand will not shake the country's
commitment to its economic reform deal with the International
Monetary Fund (IMF), according to reports reaching here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The conditions that Thailand accepted in return for a 17
billion U.S. dollar international bailout were a national
commitment that would transcend the passing of governments,
Thanong said on Sunday in Hong Kong where he was attending an
IMF-world bank meeting. (Thailand-IMF)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- U.S. Vice-President Al Gore arrived here Monday,
seeking further cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin met him at the
airport. The two men will chair a bilateral commission on economic
and technological cooperation in the Russian capital, the
Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The session, whose main task is to approve an action plan of
the Commission until 2000, will be of "principal importance,"
Chernomyrdin said. (Russia-US-Meeting)
</P>
<P>
