</P>
<P>
ALMA-ATA -- Kazakhstan will invest 2 billion U.S. dollars in
the construction of a big nuclear power station near the Balkhash
Lake, 400 kilometers to the northeast of Alma-Ata, a Kazakh
official said.
</P>
<P>
Vladimir Sergeevich Shkolnik, minister of Science and New
Technologies, told the Interfax News Agency that his country plans
to start building the nuclear power station in 1999 and complete
it in seven and a half years.
</P>
<P>
The station will have three generators, each with a generating
capacity of 640 megawatt, Shkolnik said. (Kazakhstan-Nuclear Power
Stations)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japan's newly named Management and Coordination Agency
Chief Koko Sato submitted his resignation Monday, government
spokesman Kanezo Muraoka said.
</P>
<P>
Just 11 days after his appointment to the cabinet, Sato buckled
under intense pressure and offered his resignation during a
meeting with Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto at the premier's
official residence.
</P>
<P>
Sato, 69, convicted of taking bribes in the 1970s Lockheed
payoff scandal, would be the first in the Hashimoto cabinet to
step down before completing his term. (Japan-Minister-Resignation)
