<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Help Indonesia Fight Forest Fires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia will send a
fire-fighting team to Indonesia to help put out its forest fires
which resulted in serious haze affecting Malaysia and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
The team comprising members of the Special Malaysian Assistance
Rescue Team (SMART) and Fire and Rescue Services Department
personnel would take with them equipment to draw water from
underground wells in the fire-fighting operation, Malaysian Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad told a news conference here today after
chairing a meeting of the Disaster Management and Relief
Committee.
</P>
<P>
This would be another effort by Malaysia in addition to its
assistance to help Indonesia in its cloud-seeding exercise in
tackling the haze problem.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir, who is the Director of the National Operation
Council, said that the committee studied the overall haze
situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
The haze which worsened recently led the Malaysian government
to declare on September 19 a state of haze emergency in Sarawak,
East Malaysia, which is still in force because of the very high
level of air pollution in the state.
</P>
<P>
The air quality in Sarawak was recorded at "hazardous" level
with an air pollutant index (API) reading of 569 in Kuching, the
state's capital, at 11am today compared with an API reading of 366
yesterday morning, according to an Environment Department
statement.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said, "We have agreed with the Indonesian authorities
that the Kuching airport would be used as the base in the
cloud-seeding exercise."
</P>
<P>
He said that more aircraft would be used in addition to the
existing eight in the cloud-seeding exercise in the country and
the same aircraft would be used to assist Indonesia in its
cloud-seeding exercise.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir told the news conference that the French researchers
sent here to study the haze situation in Malaysia returned to
France yesterday to draw up a form of assistance to be provided to
Malaysia to tackle the haze problem.
</P>
<P>
He said that assistance had also been sought from Japan which
had offered "jet-shooters" for the fire-fighting operation.
</P>
<P>
"We realize the problem cannot be overcome easily but we will
try our best," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir also suggested several measures that could be taken by
the public during the haze, saying that besides using masks, the
public should minimize the use of private vehicles in efforts to
reduce smoke emission.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir also said that the committee agreed that kindergartens
should be closed when the air pollutant index reading reaches 300.
</P>
<P>
He said that besides the closure of schools in the event that
the API reading reaches 400, outdoor activities should also be
reduced to prevent too much exposure to the haze.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir also made another appeal to factories to stop the
burning of wastes to help overcome the problem.
</P>
<P>
According to the API issued by the Environment Department, the
air quality throughout the country worsened with the Air
Pollutant Index (API) for 11am today showing many areas becoming
unhealthy or hazardous.
</P>
<P>
It said that besides Kuching, the air quality over Nilai in the
Negeri Sembilan state and Gombak, Kuala Lumpur's suburb was at a
hazardous level with the API Index of 306 and 301 respectively.
</P>
<P>
The air quality over Kuala Lumpur was recorded at "very
unhealthy" level with an API reading of 233 compared to 197 at 8am
today.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970922.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mount Kilimanjaro Fire Put Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 22 (Xinhua) -- An outbreak of fire
ravaging forests on the slopes of Mount Kilimanjaro for the last
two weeks has been put out, according to a news dispatch from
Moshi, northern Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The raging fire was put out owing to the concerted efforts of
the local residents and specialized fire fighting personnel, said
Lorivole Moirana, chief warden for the Kilimanjaro National Park
Authority, when he reported to Vice-President Omar Juma at the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
The fire started on September 4, affecting an estimated 109
square kilometers of bush and forest, which represented 10,900
hectares of forest cover.
</P>
<P>
A Tanzania National Parks plane was used to locate the
boundaries of the ravaging fire after it reached the 3,600 meter
altitude and was spreading towards the slopes of the mountain
which are difficult to access on foot.
</P>
<P>
The fire could have been started by campers since it started
at the Machame tourist camp, Moirana said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
