<DOCNO> XIE19970922.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Braces for Upcoming Drought Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government,
girding itself for another drought, has set aside 1.5 billion
Zimbabwe Dollars (130 million U.S. Dollars) for the import of
maize to ensure the national strategic grain reserves are full,
and that seeds for drought-resistant crops are readily available.
</P>
<P>
The financing facility will only be used if the drought, which
is expected to hit the whole of southern Africa next season,
occurs.
</P>
<P>
Kumbirai Kangai, Minister of Lands and Agriculture said at the
weekend that Zimbabwe was this time better prepared to combat the
drought than it was in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Food stocks carry-overs were higher than during the 1991/92
season when the severest drought in living memory struck.
</P>
<P>
Most of the country's water reservoirs were almost full, and
if the available supplies were used properly, there should be no
problems, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe had learnt a lesson from the great drought in 1992,
Kangai noted, hence the establishment of the national strategic
grain reserves which have a maximum capacity of 936,000 tons of
maize.
</P>
<P>
The maize was enough to feed the nation for at least four
months, which is enough to prepare for imports if there was need
to do so.
</P>
<P>
"We don't want the 1992 situation to be repeated where long
queues for mealie-meal were a common sight everywhere," he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
On maize exports, the minister said, it was government policy
not to export until the stragetic reserve was full.
</P>
<P>
"We always ensure that the strategic grain reserves are filled
at the end of each season before we can start exporting maize,"
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970922.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Farmers Compensated for Slaughtering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government has
released 764 Kwacha (about 600,000 U.S. Dollars) to compensate
farmers for slaughtering their cattle infected with contagious
bovine pleuro-pneumonia diease (CBPP) that threatens the
country's economy, Zambia Daily Mail reported today.
</P>
<P>
At a news briefing at the weekend, Edith Nawakwi, Minister of
Agriculture, Food and Fisheries told reporters that 764 million
Kwacha has been released for operations and compensation to
cattle farmers in western province whose animals will be
slaughtered in a bid to curb the spread of CBPP.
</P>
<P>
CBPP, a deadly cattle lung disease second only to rinderpest
in deaths and destruction, was first reported in Botswana, where
it has claimed hundreds of thousands of cattle. The disease now
has spread to Angola, Zambia, Tanzania and Namibia.
</P>
<P>
Since April, the Zambian government has taken urgent measures
to contain the spread of the disease by banning cattle movement
and slaughtering all the infected cattle.
</P>
<P>
Western province is the most seriously affected area where
about 200 herds have been slaughtered and 1,800 more are expected
to be killed in later months.
</P>
<P>
The agricultural minister appealed to farmers to slaughter all
their infected cattle without delay, warning that the deadly
disease is threatening directly the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
Nawakwi assured that compensation for farmers at market value
will be made immediately before the slaughter of infected cattle.
</P>
<P>
She also thanked the Food and Agriculture Organisation (FAO)
and the Netherlands government for their response to her
ministry's appeal for funds and extension activities to help
eradicate the disease and called for more support from other
cooperating partners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
