<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Backs Reforms in "Transition Countries" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Johannes Linn, the World
Bank's vice-president for Europe and Central Asia, said today that
the bank would support market-oriented reforms in the "transition
countries," or countries of the former Soviet Union and Eastern
Europe.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference here, Linn said that progress in
the transition to market-based economies varies considerably
across the East European and Central Asian countries, as do
countries' policy priorities and resulting economic growth.
</P>
<P>
"The objective of eventual membership in the European Union
(EU) unifies the challenges of many of the Central and Eastern
European countries, and in fiscal 1997 the World Bank's assistance
strategy for these countries focused on supporting them in their
preparations," said Linn, who joined the World Bank in 1993.
</P>
<P>
In response to questions from reporters, Linn said that as
these countries benefit from large private financial flows, the
World Bank's attention is focused on systemic economic issues,
increasingly through non-lending services.
</P>
<P>
For the countries of the Commonwealth of Independent States
(CIS), or the former Soviet republics, "the challenges, and thus
the assistance strategy, are different," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
He said: "Here the emphasis is to help these countries make
their fiscal adjustment more sustainable and efficient, strengthen
law enforcement, basic social services, and safety nets, and
accelerate the implementation of the numerous market-oriented
reforms that remain."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he stressed the need for all the "transition
countries" to work out right macroeconomic policies for
accelerating their economic growth. "If policy missed, one will be
quickly punished," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
