<HEADLINE> UNESCO Urges for Girls' Scientific Education in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 22 (Xinhua) -- UNESCO has urged for
girls' scientific education, saying that negative attitude
towards science subjects and poor teaching methods have adversely
affected girls and women taking up science subjects in Africa.
</P>
<P>
This was of the view of a three-day consultative meeting of
the United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural
Organization (UNESCO) last weekend.
</P>
<P>
Resolutions adopted at the meeting called for a reversal of
the trend by encouraging girls to pursue science subjects and a
complete view of science and mathematics curricula in schools.
</P>
<P>
Recommendations were made to involve more women teachers in
science subjects and their motivation.
</P>
<P>
It was observed that there is a go slow by some governments in
involving women in science and technology, suggesting an
about-turn is needed to bring scientific and technological
advancement in the new millennium. The meeting recommended for a
gender sensitive policy and commitment by respective governments
to involve women in science and technology.
</P>
<P>
The UNESCO meeting also urged for closer African cooperation
in science and technology and exchange of information. It
encouraged African countries to establish exclusive women
universities to have more female admitted to schools and higher
institutions of studies.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was attended by delegates from the Congo (K),
Ghana, Swaziland, Kenya, Uganda, Cote d'Ivoire, the Sudan and
Tanzania. 
</P>
