<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weevils Reduce Hyacinth on Ugandan Lake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The weevils introduced on
Lake Kyoga, central Uganda to control the water hyacinth have
effectively reduced the weed, local daily The New Vision reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Richard Molo from the Namulonge Agriculture Research Institute
near Kampala was quoted as saying that five years after the
weevils were put in Lake Kyoga, the once luxuriant weeds have
been reduced in size and height.
</P>
<P>
He said the height has been reduced from the average one and a
half metres to 60 centimeters.
</P>
<P>
The two species of weevils introduced on the lake in 1993 are
breeding faster than in central America, the countries of its
origin.
</P>
<P>
"Where the weevils have established themselves, there are now
mother plants without daughter plants which are being suppressed
by the weevils aggressively," said Molo.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the plants which have become individuals are
now susceptible to water wave action and are easily destroyed.
</P>
<P>
There was no longer extensive water hyacinth on the lake
because of weevil attack, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
