<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Urges Developed Economies to Act for Financial Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Minister of Finance
Liu Zhongli today urged the developed economies to make efforts
for stabilizing the global economic environment and safeguarding
the order of international financial market.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 56th Meeting of the Development Committee of
the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund (IMF) here, Liu
said regional financial crises have occurred frequently in recent
years and they have caused substantial uncertainties to developing
countries' development and the global economy.
</P>
<P>
"Although the critical instruments for developing countries to
overcome such uncertainties is to strengthen their capacity in
maintaining sound economic fundamentals, the international
community, developed countries in particular, should also be
obliged to stabilize the global economic environment and to
safeguard the order of international financial market," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Minister also noted that "developed countries
should also take into account the implications for developing
countries when formulating their domestic macro-economic policies,
especially financial policies."
</P>
<P>
He said China welcomes the consensus between the World Bank and
the IMF in their cooperation in the financial area.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that when helping the countries concerned in dealing
with their financial crisis, the two institutions could also, on
the basis of their respective comparative advantages, explore the
policy alternatives for developing countries to maintain the
stability of the financial sector in an open economy," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We urge the two institutions to encourage the joint efforts by
developed and developing countries to protect the soundness of the
global economic integration," Liu added.
</P>
<P>
Touching upon the external environment faced by developing
countries during their process of opening up, he said the
present-day international economic environment characterized by
fast growth, low inflation and low interest rates, is in general
favorable.
</P>
<P>
The majority of the developing countries are taking the
opportunity to accelerate their reforms and integration into the
world economy, he said. However, he added, "Developing countries
are faced with challenges of new risks in further opening up their
economy."
</P>
<P>
The currency turmoil which has hit some Southeast Asian
countries recently is one of the examples, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
