<HEADLINE>   Japan's Cabinet Member Resigns for Involvement in Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Japan's newly named Management
and Coordination Agency Chief Koko Sato submitted his resignation
today, government spokesman Kanezo Muraoka said.
</P>
<P>
Just 11 days after his appointment to the cabinet, Sato buckled
under intense pressure and offered his resignation during a
meeting with Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto at the premier's
official residence.
</P>
<P>
Sato, 69, convicted of taking bribes in the 1970s Lockheed
payoff scandal, would be the first in the Hashimoto cabinet to
step down before completing his term.
</P>
<P>
Sato was named as a state minister in the cabinet reshuffle on
September 11, three days after Hashimoto won a second two-year
term as president of the ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP).
</P>
<P>
His appointment to the cabinet, arousing fierce reaction that
the LDP did not anticipate, drew anger from the public, the
opposition, the Social Democratic Party (SDP) and New Party
Sakigake which are LDP's two non-cabinet allies, and even some
members within the LDP.
</P>
<P>
Sato, a member of Japan's House of Representatives, is the
first person convicted of a serious crime to join the cabinet in
the postwar period.
</P>
<P>
In May 1986, the Tokyo High Court sentenced Sato a two-year
imprisonment, charged with for taking 2 million yen (about 16,667
US dollars) of bribes in the Lockheed scandal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
