<HEADLINE> Dhaka Seeks Support to Speed up Privatization Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi government has
sought package assistance from donors for the success of its
ambitious privatization program, which was strongly opposed by
some labor unions and opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the donors make commitments in the next aid group
meeting to assist our privatization program," Privatization Board
Chairman Kazi Zafarullah told a meeting with a group of donors'
representatives here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Official sources said that assistance from the donors was
sought for three tasks -- workers' retraining, public awareness
program and payment of liabilities of the mills to be privatized.
</P>
<P>
However, the cost of the three programs, which will be placed
in the Aid Club meeting to be held here early in November, were
yet to be calculated.
</P>
<P>
To allay the apprehension aired by donors that the
privatization process might face a setback due to labor unrest and
political opposition, the government has approved the
privatization proposals of 12 state-owned enterprises (SOEs)
during the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
"These are substantial progress and the donors are extremely
impressed. They have understood that the government is firmly
committed to carrying out the privatization program," said
Zafarullah.
</P>
<P>
The Privatization Board has a target to offload a total of 106
SOEs during the current 1997-98 fiscal year. Of them, 52 were
slated to disinvest during the previous years while 54 new units
added to the list. 
</P>
</TEXT>
