<HEADLINE> Belgian Soccer Federation Called for Tough Punishment after </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The Belgian soccer
federation Sunday demanded tough legal action against rowdy fans
who invaded pitches during three top division games this weekend.
</P>
<P>
In all three incidents, fans spilled onto the field after their
clubs conceded the last goal in humiliating losses. The games were
delayed until the fans were driven back into the stands.
</P>
<P>
Jan Peeters, secretary general of the Belgian soccer
federation, said: "These people need to be punished very
seriously."
</P>
<P>
Peeters told a local radio: "We still need a repressive
framework."
</P>
<P>
In the worst incident on Saturday, police had to drive back FC
Antwerp fans, who had demolished a fence and spilled onto the
field in Westerlo after their team conceded the fifth goal in a
5-2 drubbing by the first-division newcomer.
</P>
<P>
At Sint Truiden, several dozen local fans jumped over fences
and moved threateningly to the dugout of coach Barry Hulshoff
after their team conceded the final goal in a 5-0 defeat at the
hands of reigning champion Lierse.
</P>
<P>
Late Friday, dozens of Anderlecht fans scaled the metal fences
and stormed the field of Belgium's most famous club after
Anderlecht conceded a late goal for the third home defeat in a
row, a 2-1 loss to Mouscron.
</P>
<P>
The field invasions were the worst security incidents during
the Belgian season so far. Belgium hosts the 2000 European
Championships, together with the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Peeters said: "It's an indication that Euro 2000 has to devote
attention to that problem."  
</P>
</TEXT>
