<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Growth Brings Multiple Opportunities, W.Bank Seminar Told </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 22 (Xinhua) -- China's rapid development
has brought and will continue to provide multiple opportunities to
all the countries in the world, senior officials and international
bankers attending a World Bank seminar said here today.
</P>
<P>
The sustained and fast economic growth will give rise to a huge
demand for imports and investments, according to consensus reached
at the seminar titled "China: Challenge and Prospects", which was
the opening session of a full-day program on China's economy on
the eve of the World Bank and International Monetary Fund annual
meetings.
</P>
<P>
Chen Jinhua, Chinese minister in charge of the State Planning
Commission, told more than 300 participants that China will be
able to maintain an eight percent annual growth and limit
inflation to less than five percent till early next century.
</P>
<P>
"We are confident that we can maintain such an economic
situation," he said, adding that there are favorable conditions
supporting the "high growth and low inflation" momentum.
</P>
<P>
China has a very large domestic market, and the growing need of
over a billion population for the improvement of their material
and cultural life will generate new demands which will in turn
stimulate the sustained rapid economic growth, he said.
</P>
<P>
Joseph Stiglitz, chief economist and senior vice-president of
the World Bank, agreed with Chen, citing a latest World Bank
research report that predicted China's hopes for a new century of
growth and prosperity can be met.
</P>
<P>
Forecasting that China's trade volume could reach nearly 10
percent of the world's total by 2020, Stiglitz said its rising
demand for capital and knowledge-intensive manufactures and
primary products will benefit many other countries.
</P>
<P>
Chen said that total demand for investment is estimated at
about 1.3 billion U.S. dollars in China in the next three years,
while the annual trade volume will hit 400 billion U.S. dollars by
the end of the century, with imports and exports basically
balanced.
</P>
<P>
"Such a large demand will greatly drive the growth of world
trade and economy, and provide excellent opportunities for
wide-ranging cooperation between China and the rest of the world,"
Chen said.
</P>
<P>
Holding the same view as Chen's, William Purves, chairman of
the British HSBC Holdings, stressed the importance of investing in
China with a long-term perspective.
</P>
<P>
Participating in the growth of the dynamic nation is "vital to
investors with truly international aspirations," Purves said.
</P>
<P>
Chen said a large number of joint ventures or solely foreign
funded ventures set up in China have rapidly expanded their
operations and increased their competitiveness, thus becoming the
leaders of performance among the globally distributed subsidiaries
of the multinationals.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that 294,000 foreign funded enterprises
have so far been registered in China, with a total of nearly 200
billion U.S. dollars of direct investment by overseas firms.
</P>
<P>
Some two-thirds of those enterprises are now profitable and
over 80 percent of the large and medium-sized foreign funded
enterprises are successful, Chen said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970922.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Tapioca Exports to EU to Fall Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's tapioca exports to
the European Union would fall next year because Thai products
would be more expensive as a result of the depreciation of the
German mark against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The EU is also expected to grow more of its own tapioca,
according to Boonchai Srichaiyongpanich, president of the Tapioca
Trade Association of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Tapioca is one of Thailand's main agricultural exports along
with rubber, rice, frozen prawns and sugar.
</P>
<P>
Boonchai put EU tapioca imports at 200,000-250,000 tons per
month next year, compared with the current 300,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Thai tapioca manufacturers face a lack of funds for
buying fresh cassava from farmers, Boonchai said.
</P>
<P>
Commercial banks have lowered the amount of loan money
available to each manufacturer by 50-70 percent while at the same
time raising interest rates beyond 20 percent, the Bangkok Post
today quoted Boonchai as saying.
</P>
<P>
Boonchai urged the government to step in to help manufacturers
secure enough funds before the next cassava crop comes on the
market beginning next month.
</P>
<P>
The association has also urged the Bank for Agriculture and
Agricultural Cooperatives to extend the debt repayment period for
tapioca farmers. This would lessen the burden on farmers if
manufacturers are unable to buy as much cassava as usual.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
