<HEADLINE> Chinese Minister Urges World Bank to Support Developing Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hong Kong, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Minister of Finance
Liu Zhongli today urged the World Bank to provide direct financial
support to the infrastructure projects in the developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 56th Meeting of the Development Committee of
the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund (IMF) here, Liu
noted that the Chinese government pays increasing attention to
the global issue of anti-corruption.
</P>
<P>
"We support the World Bank to implement the action plan in an
active and pragmatic way. Having said that, we are of the view
that the bank should continue to maintain and expand its
traditional lending operations, and to provide direct financial
support to the public financed infrastructure projects," Liu said.
</P>
<P>
He said: "Anti-corruption and governance improvement are issues
drawing attention from the governments all over the world
including the Chinese government."
</P>
<P>
However, Liu pointed out that sovereign countries' leading
position in domestic anti-corruption actions and international
cooperation in this field should be respected. The World Bank and
the IMF could provide assistance only upon the request from the
governments of their member-countries, he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he expressed support for the recent actions of the
two international institutions in preventing corruption.
</P>
<P>
Touching upon operations of the Multilateral Investment
Guarantee Authority (MIGA), Liu said: "We have always been
supportive of MIGA's capital increase, and look forward to an
early solution." "The Chinese Government is ready to assume its
due responsibility to this end," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also said the Heavily Indebted Poor Countries Initiative
(HIPC) has moved into the stage of implementation. "We hope that
the concrete consensus will be reached between the multilateral
creditors and the Paris Club on the burden-sharing modality, which
will be able to reflect the principle of equitable
burden-sharing," he noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
