<HEADLINE> India Plans Reform in Oil Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 22 (Xinhua) -- India's Union Petroleum
Ministry, oil companies and international merchant bankers have
evolved a consensus on a reform package for the country's oil
sector, an informed source said here today.
</P>
<P>
The proposed measures include decanalization of crude imports,
delicensing of the refining industry and the establishment of a
commission on oil regulation.
</P>
<P>
After two days of talks and discussions, participants agreed
that the government should free imports and exports of oil
products, with public sector units having the authority to
administer and monitor long-term government-to-government
contracts, grant refining companies rights to transportation
links, ports and jetties as well as free retail sales of petroleum
products.
</P>
<P>
A report will be submitted to the Petroleum Ministry for formal
consideration soon.  
</P>
</TEXT>
