<HEADLINE> Kazakhstan to Develop Nuclear Power Stations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA-ATA, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Kazakhstan will invest 2
billion U.S. dollars in the construction of a big nuclear power
station near the Balkhash Lake, 400 kilometers to the northeast of
Alma-Ata, a Kazakh official said.
</P>
<P>
Vladimir Sergeevich Shkolnik, minister of Science and New
Technologies, told the Interfax News Agency that his country
plans to start building the nuclear power station in 1999 and
complete it in seven and a half years.
</P>
<P>
The station will have three generators, each with a generating
capacity of 640 megawatt, Shkolnik said.
</P>
<P>
An international consortium will be responsible for the
construction fund and the Kazakh government will provide 340
million dollars in the first stage of the construction.
</P>
<P>
The minister, also president of the Academy of Science, said
Kazakhstan also plans to build four to six small nuclear power
stations in the western and central parts of the country before
2030, with a total investment of 5-6 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
