<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Thailand has appointed four
committees to implement action plans to rehabilitate the country's
economy, according to a Bangkok Post report today.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund (IFM) and the World Bank, which
have brokered a 17.2 billion US dollar package rescue credit line
for Thailand, have proposed restructuring the Thai economy,
spanning industry, agriculture, commerce, investment,
privatization and legal infrastructures.
</P>
<P>
The two international financial organizations are working with
the Thai government to formulate strategies to restructure the
whole economy.
</P>
<P>
The restructuring is aimed at boosting the country's
competitive standing and ensuring sustainable growth.
</P>
<P>
The restructuring plan will cover upgrading technology in the
industrial and agricultural sectors, boosting productivity,
training programs for unskilled labor and measures to boost
exports and deal with unemployment.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government is scheduled to propose its first economic
rehabilitation program at the end of October, and by the end of
this month, measures dealing with the rehabilitation of 58
suspended finance firms are due to be announced.  
