<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Annual Coal Output Reaches 51 Million Tons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Coal production in Indonesia
currently reaches about 51 million tons per year, making it
capable of assuming the role of an important alternative energy
sources in the near future, an official said.
</P>
<P>
In 1980, national coal production stood at only 0.3 million
tons, while consumption totaled about 0.2 million tons, Soedjojo,
an official from the ministry of mines and energy, said here
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Domestic coal consumption for this year is estimated to reach
13 million tons, which means that the country will experience a
coal surplus of around 38 million tons, local press today quoted
the official as saying.
</P>
<P>
The production surplus will mostly be exported, he said,
referring to recent data which showed that in 1996 Indonesia
exported 36 million tons of coal.
</P>
<P>
Coal is also widely used as an energy source for some power
plants in the country. By the end of 1994, coal had helped
generate 2,100 megawatts of electricity.
</P>
<P>
According to Soedjoko, by the end of 2008, about 24,500
megawatts of electricity in Indonesia will be generated by the use
of coal.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
