<HEADLINE> HK Investors Rebuilding Dilapidated Bungalows in Tianjin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Investors from Hong Kong have
shown a great zeal toward reconstruction of dilapidated bungalows
in Tianjin, the largest port city in north China.
</P>
<P>
Information from the Tianjin Municipal Commission of Foreign Trade
and Economic Cooperation revealed that HK investors have started
436 real estate businesses, which involve an agreed use of 1.52
billion U.S. dollars of overseas funds, accounting for a half of
their respective total for overseas businesses and for the
contractual use of overseas funds.
</P>
<P>
New World Group and Henderson Properties Co. Ltd. have raced
far ahead of other investors from Hong Kong. On June 25 of last
year, New World Group signed a contract with Tianjin over
demolishing dilapidated bungalows on an area of 42 hectares in
the city's Nanshi District within five years.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, New World Group will also carry out real estate
development on 160 hectares of land in Tianjin's other districts.
Before this, it has cooperated with Tianjin in constructing 1.2
million sq m of flats under the Comfortable Living
Project, which is aimed at providing urban families with low and
moderate incomes. So far, a village of flats for teachers, with a
combined floor space of 240,000 sq m, has been completed.
</P>
<P>
Henderson Properties Co. Ltd. has also signed a contract with
Tianjin to make investment for rebuilding 2.24 million sq m of
dilapidated bungalows in Tianjin's old city area.
</P>
<P>
As the largest old industrial city in north China, Tianjin has
a lot of dilapidated bungalows that need to be reconstructed.
Owing to a lack of funds, the Tianjin Municipal Government decided to
mainly rely on overseas investment to reconstruct all dilapidated
bungalows in the city in five years beginning from 1994.
</P>
<P>
The city government has drafted a wide range of preferential
policies to encourage investors from overseas to make investment
in this aspect. The policies include exemption of fees for
government-provided supporting facilities and its responsibility of
pre-stage removal work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
