<HEADLINE> Industrial Corridor in China's Hainan Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, September 22 (Xinhua) -- An industrial corridor has
taken shape in the western part of south China's island province
of Hainan, with the groundbreaking or completion of a number of
projects each costing hundreds of millions of yuan.
</P>
<P>
The petrochemical industry is the corridor's focus, a local
official said.
</P>
<P>
The first phase construction of a natural gas fertilizer
project with an investment of 2.5 billion yuan has been
completed. Its annual output is expected to be 300,000 tons of
synthetic hydrogen nitride and 520,000 tons of urea.
</P>
<P>
The second phase will start next year at a cost of 2.8
billion yuan. It is set to be operational by 2000, with an annual
production of 450,000 tons of synthetic hydrogen nitride and
800,000 tons of urea.
</P>
<P>
The Yangpu Development Zone is an important part of the
corridor, and is expected to turn into a production base for
petrochemistry, food processing and chemical fiber, according to
the official.
</P>
<P>
The industrial corridor is also a base for building materials
and metallurgy. A cement plan with an investment of one billion yuan
and an annual production of 820,000 tons will be put into
operation at the end of this year. A 600-million-yuan plant is
already open and is set to produce 100,000 tons of light
cold-rolled sheeting a year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
