<HEADLINE> Death Toll from Starvation, Cholera Rises in Indonesia's Irian Jaya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The number of victims who
died of starvation and cholera rife in some subdistricts of
Indonesia's Irian Jaya province, has increased to 251, local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Jayawijaya district head Jb. Wenas said last night that till
Sunday afternoon the number of the victims rose to 251 people.
</P>
<P>
The worst-hit villages are Silimo, Pasema, Tangua, Siru, Soba,
Kurupu, Mapenduma and Mbua in Jayawijaya district, all of them
situated in remote areas, said the reports.
</P>
<P>
The breakout of cholera and food shortage started in mid-August
following a lingering drought in the country.
</P>
<P>
The number of the victims was predicted to increase as the
local people drank dirty water making them affected by cholera
because they lacked clear water for drink.
</P>
<P>
The local government had tried hard to send relief assistance
in the form of among other things foods and medicines as well as
physicians but it failed due to the thick smoke making the
aircraft carrying the relief aid unable to land on the disaster
sites.  
</P>
