<HEADLINE> Brazil Sweeps Gold of U-17 World Cup Soccer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Brazil trounced Ghana 2-1
Sunday to carry away the gold cup at the 4th Under-17 World
Championship, avenging its loss to the African powerhouse at the
1995 final.
</P>
<P>
Since the kickoff, the sturdy Ghananians overpowered the
Brazilians with a storm of long shots and clipped their edge in
delivering fast passes.
</P>
<P>
In the 39th minute, Wisdom Abbey converted a short pass to a
left kick, passing over goalkeeper Fabio Maciel and slipping the
ball into the net.
</P>
<P>
The first half ended with the African title-holder taking a 1-0
lead. After the half time, Brazilians considerably sped up their
offensive and equalized 16 minutes into the second half.
</P>
<P>
In the 61st minute, Osel Boateng stopped a long shot only to
push it to Brazilian Matuzalem Silva, who dodged the defenders and
kicked it into the net, leaving the Ghanian goalie running for the
ball.
</P>
<P>
Boosted by the 1-1 tie, Brazilians went on a shooting spree and
could have well scored if the Ghanian guardian had done his job
less attentively.
</P>
<P>
But the crushing avalanche soon turned into a defensive game,
as Fabio Pinto, Brazil's winning-card, was given the only red card
of the match and fouled out.
</P>
<P>
Only three minutes before the final whistle, and after the
Ghanians flexed their muscles, the Brazilians netted their second
unexpected goal, by Andrey Mayr.
</P>
<P>
The South American samba dancers finally avenged their twice
defeat to the African talents.
</P>
<P>
In their two encounters at the Under-17 World Championship,
Ghana beat Brazil 2-1 in the quarter-finals in Italy in 1991 and
closely shaved Brazil 3-2 in the final in Ecuador in 1995.
</P>
<P>
In another match played Sunday before the final, Spain beat
Germany 2-1 to take the third place.
</P>
<P>
In the 31st minute, Ander Aranceta Lucena scored the first goal
for Spain with a header provided by Franquelo Sousa.
</P>
<P>
Germany got even in the 44th minute from a penalty kick by
Silvio Adzic.
</P>
<P>
Five minutes before time, German goalkeeper Roman Weidenfeller
managed to stop a penalty kick from Sousa but failed to catch the
ball. Sousa retook the ball and pushed it into the net.
</P>
<P>
Altogether 16 teams played 32 matches at the Under-17 World
Championship, which started since September 4 in four Egyptian
cities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
