<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Witnesses Stable Increase in Tax Revenues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 22 (Xinhua) -- China netted 54.05 billion
yuan (6.51 billion US dollars) of revenues from industrial and
commercial taxes in August, a rise of 12.9 percent over the same
period last year, "China Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
In August, business taxes climbed to 9.79 billion yuan, up 49.5
percent, while stamp duty rose to 1.97 billion yuan, up 39.2
percent. Out of the total stamp duty collected last month, duty
from stock trading was 1.79 billion yuan, up 42.1 percent from the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Individual income taxes also registered a fast growth of 24
percent to 2.09 billion yuan last month.
</P>
<P>
However, the domestic value-added and consumption taxes, two
major taxes in China, totaled 29.83 billion yuan in August, showing
a slight 5.7 percent growth rate, which is six percentage points down
from the average growth rate in the previous seven months of this
year, the newspaper quoted information from the State
Administration of Taxation as saying.
</P>
<P>
Poor efficiency of State enterprises, especially in key tax
sources sectors, and growing delayed taxable payments are blamed
for the slowdown of the increase in the two taxes.
</P>
<P>
The taxation agency urged tax authorities at different levels
to intensify their efforts to collect taxes and strengthen tax
audits to avoid tax evasion and ensure the tax target is met.
</P>
<P>
Tax collectors are required to pay special attention to key
tax sources such as cigarettes, rolled steel and building
materials sectors.
</P>
<P>
By the end of August, the industrial and commercial tax revenue
reached 477.34 billion yuan, 18.6 percent more than the same
period last year and finishing 68.7 percent of the annual plan.
</P>
<P>
The goal for industrial and commercial tax revenues for the
year of 1997 is set at 695 billion yuan, according to the
information. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970922.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Pledges to Improve Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 22 (Xinhua) -- China's capital has pledged
to meet state pollution standards by the year 2000 and improve its
environment.
</P>
<P>
Municipal departments say that Beijing will improve the 60 key
industrial polluters in the urban area this year and that those
that fail to meet requirements will have to stop production or be
closed.
</P>
<P>
The city has also demanded that 600 boilers above 10 tons
reduce the amount of coal used and the emission of dust and smoke
by using energy-saving methods and efficient dust removers and
desulphurization methods.
</P>
<P>
All boilers in the downtown area will have to use natural gas
from a pipeline from northwest China to decrease the discharge of
sulphur dioxide and smoke.
</P>
<P>
Since June 1, the city has banned the use of leaded gas and
Automobiles that fail to meet exhaust standards are not allowed on
streets, officials say.
</P>
<P>
The city has spent 63.6 billion yuan (about 8 billion US
dollars) on urban infrastructure over the past five years for
sewage and garbage treatment plants and heating supplies.
</P>
<P>
The city's rate for waste-water treatment is now 21 percent,
and garbage treatment rate 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
Beijing spent 1.5 billion yuan on controlling industrial
pollution in the past five years, relocating 78 heavy polluters
and closing a number of factories and workshops with serious
pollution problems.
</P>
<P>
Although 330,000 residents and more than three million migrant
people have been added to the city's population, and the number of
automobiles has doubled over the past five years, Beijing's
environmental quality has not deteriorated, officials say, and
they believe the city can meet its goals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970922.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Future of Satellites Examined </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Beijing television viewers
have a lot more selection on their tubes these days, according to
today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The local cable system can now broadcast programs produced by
Zhejiang, Shandong, Sichuan, Hunan and several other provincial
television stations.
</P>
<P>
And Beijing doctors can now see patients in other major Chinese
cities, consult with counterparts in other regions and direct
complicated operations -- without ever leaving the city.
</P>
<P>
It's possible due to communications satellites.
</P>
<P>
Experts and executives from more than 60 Chinese and 30 foreign
satellite-related-manufacturing companies teamed up with research
institutes and organizations which use satellites to try and find
answers to these questions.
</P>
<P>
They converged on Beijing last week for the international
technical exchange seminar on satellite communications,
broadcasting and television (China Satcom '97).
</P>
<P>
The seminar's purpose was to prepare Chinese satellite users
for potential technical problems, market competition and various
other issues they may face next century, said Yang Qianli, a
deputy chairman of China Users Association of Satellite
Communications, Broadcasting and Television (CUASCBT).
</P>
<P>
The organization co-ordinated the four-day seminar, which
concluded on Friday.
</P>
<P>
During the seminar, the participants discussed lastest
developments in satellite communications technology.
</P>
<P>
There are presently five major satellite communications players
in China and competition has intensified.
</P>
<P>
The five firms include two Hong Kong-based companies, AsiaSat
and APT Satellite Holdings Ltd, and three mainland companies,
China Telecommunications Broadcast Satellite Corp (ChinaSat),
China Orient Telecommunications Satellite Co Ltd and Sino
Satellite Communications Co Ltd.
</P>
<P>
Large American firms -- including Motorola, TRW, Loral and
Qualcomm -- are now developing their own satellite-based mobile
communications systems such as Iridium, ICO, Odyssey and
Globalstar. enditem


nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
