<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Introduce Flower Cloning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists will
introduce cloning technology to good fine strains of rare and
valuable flowers.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the Chinese Academy of Foresty Sciences revealed
that the academy recently established a research center in Suzhou,
in east China's Jiangsu Province, to carry out related research.
</P>
<P>
Chinese roses, azaleas, and cold-resistant plants have been
included on the list for prospective cloning, with the
aforementioned sources pointing out that the academy will buy
patents and obtain needed facilities from abroad to promote
related experiments.
</P>
<P>
China is currently 20-odd years behind developed countries in
terms of flower planting technology. Therefore, the State Science
and Technology Commission has drafted a plan to open up research
centers in east China and other regions with proper soil and
climatic conditions to increase flower exports.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
