<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT September 22 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB -- Croatian Foreign Minister Mate Granic Sunday strongly
condemned Thursday's car bombing in Mostar, describing it as a
form of the most ruthless terrorist activity launched against the
consolidation and peace process of Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
A powerful explosion, which went off near the police station in
the Croat-controlled western Mostar, injured 50
people. (Croatia-Bombing-Condemnation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
GENEVA -- The total amount of the global foreign direct
investment (FDI) reached 349 billion U.S. dollars in 1996, a 10
percent rise over 1995, said a United Nations report published
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, 208 billion dollars went into developed countries
and 129 billion dollars into developing countries, the United
Nations Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD) said in its
1997 World Investment Report.
</P>
<P>
China is still the second largest FDI recipient in the world,
absorbing 42 billion dollars, which accounted for over 50 percent
of the total amount of the FDI inflows into Asia last year. The
United States remained to be the largest FDI recipient by
attracting 85 billion dollars in 1996, the report said. (UN-Global
Investment)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TIRANA -- The third contingent of Albanian troops left by plane
Saturday to join the NATO-led peacekeeping mission in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
This contingent of 35 troops, headed by a lieutenant colonel,
will receive a one-month training in Germany before going to
Bosnia for a six-month mission, an Albanian TV report said.
(Albania-Bosnia-Peacekeepers)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- Chinese Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister
Qian Qichen arrived here Saturday evening to attend the 52nd
session of the General Assembly of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Qian, heading a Chinese delegation, will give a speech on
China's views on current international situation as well as
China's domestic developments during the general debate of the
Assembly which is scheduled to begin Monday, a spokesman for the
Chinese Mission to the United Nations said.
</P>
<P>
The 52nd session of the U.N. General Assembly opened last
Tuesday. The session is expected to last until mid-December with
its focus on the reform of the world body.(China-FM-UN)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME -- An estimated one million Italians flocked to Milan and
Venice Saturday for a massive union-organized demonstration
against secession. (Italy-Rally)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
GENEVA -- The Royal Dutch/Shell group topped the list of the
100 biggest transnational corporations (TNCs) for the fifth
running year, the United Nations reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The 100 multinational giants has 1.7 trillion dollars of assets
in their foreign affiliates, representing about a fifth of the
world's total foreign assets.
</P>
<P>
The European Union, the United States and Japan are home to 87
of the 100 leading TNCs and controlled 88 percent of their foreign
assets. (UN-Company-Rankings) 
</P>
</TEXT>
