<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Becomes World's Second Largest FDI Recipient </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 22 (Xinhua) -- China attracted a record 42.3
billion US dollars of foreign direct investment (FDI) last year,
remaining the second largest recipient of foreign capital in the
world, according to a report of the United Nations Conference on
Trade and Development (UNCTAD).
</P>
<P>
The report, which was released in Beijing recently, said that
the figure accounts for about half of the foreign direct
investment in Asia last year.
</P>
<P>
It attributes the increase of the FDI in China to the
ever-growing market, successful overall economic reform measures,
smooth "soft-landing" of the national economy and China's
preferential policies for foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
Another important reason is that foreign investors rushed to
launch investment projects before the Chinese government abrogates
some of the preferential treatment, like customs tariff and tax
reduction in the first half of last year.
</P>
<P>
After China, the report said, Singapore was the second largest
recipient of FDI in Asia, attracting nine billion US dollars in
1996.
</P>
<P>
Last year more than 120 billion US dollars of FDI flew into the
developing countries, and some 200 billion US dollars went into
the developed countries. Of the latter, 84.6 billion US dollars of
FDI was invested in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The report also noted that Asia has emerged as an important
source of FDI. FDI from Asia amounted to 47 billion US
dollars. Hong Kong alone invested 26 billion US dollars in other
places. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
