<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Non-Trade Foreign Exchange Up in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The amount of non-trade
foreign exchange in China's economic center in the first half of
the year increased nearly 38 percent from the same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
This comes from the rapid development and opening up of the
local tourism, finance, and real estate industries. These three,
along with culture and arts now contribute 34 percent of the local
non-trade foreign exchange, 0.6 percentage points higher than for
the same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Every day in Shanghai, tourists exchange a large amount of
foreign currency for renminbi with a third of which coming from
credit cards, helping commercial banks get income from service
charges.
</P>
<P>
Foreign banks in the Pudong New Area are now allowed to do
renminbi business, a move that has encouraged many foreign banks
to move into the area, giving a boost to real estate as a channel
for more non-trade foreign exchange locally. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
