<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Investment for Science and Technology in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Funding for China's
scientific and technological development maintained a good pace,
swelling beyond blast year's figures, Today's China Daily said.
</P>
<P>
Research and Development Funding for institutes, enterprises
and colleges and universities rose to 33.2 billion yuan (4 billion
US dollars) in 1996, a 13.6 percent increase over 1995, the State
Statistics Bureau reported over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The Basic research and High-tech Department, under the State
Science and Technology Commission, attributed the rise in
investment to the government's emphasis on basic science
development during the past few years.
</P>
<P>
The State allocated 60 million yuan (7 million US dollars)
annually on average, during the Ninth Five-Year Plan Period
(1996-2000) to support training for scientists involved in basic
research.
</P>
<P>
More than 90 percent of the funds are being used and will
continue to be used for establishing training centers. And the
remaining money will be allocated to train scientists involved in
major projects.
</P>
<P>
The bureau's statistics indicate there is now a multichannel
funding process for scientific and technological
development. Previously, such projects received money solely from
the government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
