<HEADLINE> Environmental Protection in Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The tourist spot of
Zhangjiajie in central China's Hunan province has spent more than
20 million yuan on pollution controls in the past two years,
increasing sewage treatment and solid waste utilization rates.
</P>
<P>
The city has had 130 anti-pollution projects for controlling
waste gas and banning fireworks in urban areas, and coal-fired
boilers have been provided with desulphurization devices.
</P>
<P>
Zhangjiajie has China's first national forest park. In 1992,
the UNESCO included the city's Wulingyuan Scenic Zone on its world
natural heritage list.
</P>
<P>
In the past decade, the city has had a number of environmental
protection regulations and a network of more than 200 people has
been established at the grassroots level. It has expanded its
nature reserves area to 1,007 sq.km., providing protection for
more than 4,000 species of wild animals and plants.
</P>
<P>
After several years of afforestation work, the city's forest
coverage rate is 64 percent. As a result of this, there were 1.2
million tourists in the first eight months of this year, providing
some 400 million yuan (about 50 million US dollars) in revenues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
