<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Explains Reform Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hong Kong, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Zhu
Rongji said here today that China's reform should be conducted in
phases, starting with easy areas and proceeding to difficult ones.
</P>
<P>
China's reform and opening-up over the past 20 years have
brought about enormous tangible benefits to the Chinese people and
a much stronger economy in the country, and also helped the country
integrate itself gradually with the world economy, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
Zhu was making an address in English at the 56th Meeting of the
Development Committee of the World Bank/International Monetary
Fund in Hong Kong, a special administrative region of China.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese vice-premier stressed that the policy of reform and
opening-up has been deeply rooted in the hearts of the Chinese
people and is "irreversible". He also referred to the reform as
something unprecedented in terms of both complexity and scale.
</P>
<P>
A method of "gradual advance" should be adopted in China's
reform efforts rather than a "particular reform measure going
ahead in isolation," he said. "Experiments should be carried out
before popularization."
</P>
<P>
Explaining other aspects of the basic experience China has
gained in the reform, the vice-premier said political and social
stability is a precondition for the reform and opening-up and
economic reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
"We have all along given equal importance to reform,
development and stability and properly handled the relationship
among the three through a series of effective measures," he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, China has succeeded in maintaining a steady
economic growth through improved macroeconomic regulation and
control and economic restructuring, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government also adheres to the principle of being
practical and realistic, proceeding from China's specific national
conditions rather than blindly copying from textbooks or other
countries' models, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that "gradual advance" does not mean delaying,
nor following a beaten track or losing good opportunities.
</P>
<P>
"We give people time to observe and encourage them to carry out
experiments. Once we have obtained experience and reached
consensus, we will unswervingly advance the reform in a timely
manner," Zhu stressed.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese vice-premier, who arrived here Sunday at the
invitation of World Bank President James Wolfensohn, will deliver
a keynote speech at an international seminar later today on
China's economic prospects in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The annual meetings of the World Bank and the IMF are scheduled
for September 23-25 in Hong Kong.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970922.0241 </DOCNO>
