<HEADLINE> Single-Engine Plane Crash Kills Four in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 21 (Xinhua) -- A single-engine airplane
crashed into a medical office building shortly after taking off
Sunday in southern California of the United States, killing all
four people aboard and setting the building on fire.
</P>
<P>
But no one on the ground was injured.
</P>
<P>
The Beechcraft Sundowner crashed into the roof of the
three-story building at about 10:30 a.m. after leaving the
Torrance airport, about 12 miles south of downtown Los Angeles,
California, said Jerry Johnston, regional operations officer for
the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA).
</P>
<P>
Fire Captain John Vosper said the building apparently was
unoccupied at the time.
</P>
<P>
Firefighters extinguished the blaze within a couple of hours,
news reports said.
</P>
<P>
Investigators from the FAA and the National Transportation
Safety Board had not determined the cause of the crash, and the
victims' identities were not known. 
</P>
</TEXT>
