<HEADLINE> Parisien Returns to U.S. Ski Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Former world champion
Julie Parisien quit the Pro Race tour on Sunday to return to the
U.S. Ski Team.
</P>
<P>
The move would mostly extend the U.S. chances of winning the
gold in the Nagano Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
Parisien was the world slalom champion in 1992. In the
Albertville Olympics that year, she led after the first run, but
finished fourth. She quit the ski team in 1994 to turn pro, and
has dominated the pro tour ever since.
</P>
<P>
While Picabo Street and Tommy Moe are champion downhillers, the
U.S. ski team has no current international winners in slalom or
giant slalom. Street and Moe are both returning from injuries,
which leaves their Olympic medal hopes in question.
</P>
<P>
Parisien may be the best U.S. hope for a gold in the slalom and
giant slalom. 
</P>
