<DOCNO> XIE19970922.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mystery of Cliff Coffins in Southwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archaeologists have
finally solved the mystery of the cliff-hanging coffins in
Gongxian County in southwest China's Sichuan province.
</P>
<P>
There are over 200 cliff-hanging coffins that date from the Jin
Dynasty to the middle of the Ming Dynasty (3rd to 16th century
A.D.). They were placed on a rock face or in caves from 50 to 150
meters high, and caused people to wonder for a long time about how
people hung the coffins at such a height.
</P>
<P>
Ding Tianci, a historian from the Culture Bureau of Sichuan's
Yibin city, has developed a new theory to solve the mystery, which
has been accepted by various historians. Basically he says that
people got the coffins there by building a plank road along the
face of the cliff.
</P>
<P>
Ding said that archaeologists have found many holes, chiseled
in the cliffs in orderly fashion near coffins. He explains that it
was the custom to hang coffins on cliffs and was an effective
means of keeping the corpses from being disturbed by animals and
other people.
</P>
<P>
Historians used to take it for granted that hanging coffins on
the cliff face was the custom of the Bo people, but new research
has shown that it was the Liao, another ethnic group that has
disappeared. But, further studies are required to solve this
problem.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
