<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Australian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Australian newspapers published today:
</P>
<P>
The Australian:
</P>
<P>
-- Every child will be tested for literacy skills every two
years under a national plan endorsed by the nation's education
ministers Sunday, despite the federal government's refusal to give
513 million Australian dollars (369.36 million US dollars) in
extra funding.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald
</P>
<P>
-- The federal government is facing its second major defeat
over plans to break the power of the Maritime Union of Australia
(MUA) with a new company preparing to employ union-only labor on
Sydney's waterfront. The Hong Kong based shipping giant Orient
Overseas Container Line is finalizing details with the MUA to
begin a new stevedoring operation.
</P>
<P>
The Age
</P>
<P>
-- Inflation is dead, the governor of the Reserve Bank, Ian
Macfarlane says so, the official statistics say so. Ok, then why
are prices of so many goods and services still going up as fast as
they did a decade ago, just last week Medicare Private announced
rises of up to 20 percent in health insurance charges, the price
of milk and cream rose almost 10 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
