<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Opposition Suffers Setback in Local Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Germany's main opposition party
Social Democratic Party (SPD) suffered a major setback today in
the Hamburg local parliament election which was viewed as a test
of voters's sentiments in the run-up to Germany's 1998 national
elections.
</P>
<P>
According to preliminary television projections, the SPD won
just 36.8 percent of the vote in the election on Sunday, 3.6
percent less than in the last local election four years ago and
its worst result in the post-war era.
</P>
<P>
Although the SPD still retained its position as the strongest
party in Hamburg, the veteran SPD mayor, Henning Voscherau,
quickly announced that he would quit his post to take
responsibility for the setback. Voscherau have been mayor of
Hamburg, Germany's second largest city, for the past ten years.
</P>
<P>
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl's Christian Democratic Union
(CDU) got a lift from the Sunday election after scoring 30.6
percent of the vote, some 5.5 percent more than in the last
election in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The Greens, which is the second largest opposition party in
Bonn, came in third in Hamburg with 13.6 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
The far-right German People's Union boosted its score to about
4.8 percent but would still be excluded from parliament.
</P>
<P>
Under Germany's proportional representation voting system, a
party must win at least five percent of the vote in order to enter
the parliament.
</P>
<P>
The Statt Party, which has served as the coalition partner for
the SPD in Hamburg during the past four years, as well as the Free
Democratic Party (FDP), the junior partner in Kohl's ruling
coalition in Bonn, also failed to clear the five-percent hurdle to
win parliament seats in Hamburg.
</P>
<P>
German media predicted that the SPD was now likely to link with
the Greens to form the next local government in Hamburg, though
the CDU had also expressed its willingness to form a grand
coalition with the SPD.
</P>
<P>
A spokeswoman of the Greens said in Bonn that the results of
the Hamburg election boosted the chances for a SPD-Greens
coalition government in Bonn next year.
</P>
<P>
The Greens have ruled with the SPD in several German states in
recent years and have expressed the hope to join hands with the
latter to remove Kohl from power in the next German national
elections due in September next year.
</P>
<P>
However, Kohl's CDU party, which have been trailing the SPD in
popularity in all opinion polls recently, was apparently
encouraged by the Hamburg election. CDU General-Secretary Peter
Hintze said in Bonn that the SPD was punished today for blocking
government's proposals for major reforms in Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
