<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Acute Skill Shortages In UK Fuels Inflation Fears </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Declining unemployment in
Britain is causing acute skills shortages, with more than three
quarters of firms struggling to find suitable staff to fill
vacancies, according to a survey published today.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe that the survey by recruitment
specialist Reed Personnel Services is likely to ring alarm bells
at the Bank of England which has the power to set basic rates
since Labor came to power last May.
</P>
<P>
Following data last week that showed unemployment fell below
1.5 million for the first time in 17 years and average earnings
rose 4.5 percent in August from 4.25 percent in July, Reed's
report may add to pressure for higher interest rates.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, 76 percent of 555 organizations
questioned by Reed were suffering from skill shortages, 8 percent
more than six months ago, when the survey was first conducted.
</P>
<P>
In spite of sluggish export demand, the sector suffering most
was manufacturing, where 86 percent of firms reported difficulty
getting the right people, compared with 64 percent in April.
</P>
<P>
The problem was most acute in medium-sized companies, where 83
percent of businesses were unable to find the right staff,
compared with 78 percent of large companies and 77 percent of
small ones.
</P>
<P>
People most in demand were those with technical and
professional skills, like accountants, engineers and information
technology specialists, but there were also shortages of clerical
staff and others, said the survey.  
</P>
</TEXT>
